    content:
      'Jack and John have decided to play a game. They will be rolling a die\nseven times. One roll of a die is considered as one round of the game.\nOn each round, John agrees to pay Jack &#36;4 if $1$ or $2$ is rolled, Jack\nagrees to pay John &#36;2 if $3,4,5$ or $6$ is rolled, and who is paid wins\nthe round. In the end, who earns money wins the game.\n\n- Show that the probability that Jack wins exactly two rounds is\n$\\dfrac{224}{729}$.  <span class="marks">[3]</span>\n\n- \n  - Explain why the total number of outcomes for the results of the\nseven rounds is $128$.\n  - Expand $(1 + y)^7$ and choose a suitable value of $y$ to prove\nthat\n\n    $$\n    128 = \\binom{7}{0} + \\binom{7}{1} + \\binom{7}{2} + \\binom{7}{3} + \\binom{7}{4} + \\binom{7}{5} + \\binom{7}{6} + \\binom{7}{7}. \\vspace{-0.5em}\n    $$\n\n  - Give a meaning of the equality above in the context of the\nseven\nrounds.<span class="marks">[4]</span>\n\n\n- \n  - Find the expected amount of money earned by each player in the\ngame.\n  - Who is expected to win the game?\n  - Is this game fair? Justify your answer. <span class="marks">[3]</span>\n\n\n- Jack and John have decided to play the game again.\n  \n  - Find an expression for the probability that John wins five\nrounds on the first game and two rounds on the second game. Give\nyour answer in the form\n\n    $$\n    \\binom{7}{r}^2\\bigg[\\frac{1}{3}\\bigg]^s\\bigg[\\frac{2}{3}\\bigg]^t \\vspace{0.25em}\n    $$\n\n    where the values of $r,s$ and $t$ are to be found.\n  - Use your answer to (d) (i) and seven similar expressions to\nwrite down the probability that John wins a total of seven\nrounds over two games as the sum of eight probabilities.\n  - Hence prove that\n\n    $$\n    \\binom{14}{7} = \\sum_{k = 0}^7 \\binom{7}{k}^2. \\vspace{-0.5em} \n    $$\n\n    <span class="marks">[9]</span>\n\n\n- Now Jack and John roll a die $12$ times. Let $A$ denote the number\nof rounds Jack wins. The expected value of $A$ can be written as\n\n  $$\n  \\mathrm{E}[A] = \\sum_{r=0}^{12} r\\binom{12}{r} \\left[\\dfrac{a^{12-r}}{b^{12}}\\right] \\vspace{-0.25em}\n  $$\n\n  \n  - Find the value of $a$ and $b$.\n  - Differentiate the expansion of $(1 + y)^{12}$ to prove that the\nexpected\nnumber of rolls Jack wins is $4$. <span class="marks">[6]</span>\n\n\n',
    markScheme:
      '\n- The probability that Jack wins a round is $\\dfrac{1}{3}$.\nHence the probability that Jack wins exactly two rounds is\n\n  $$\n  \\begin{aligned}\n  \\binom{7}{2}\\bigg[\\dfrac{1}{3}\\bigg]^2\\bigg[\\dfrac{2}{3}\\bigg]^5 &= \\bigg[\\dfrac{7\\cdot6}{2}\\bigg]\\bigg[\\dfrac{1}{3^2}\\bigg]\\bigg[\\dfrac{2^5}{3^5}\\bigg]  \\\\[5pt]\n  &= \\dfrac{7\\cdot2^5}{3^6} \\\\[9pt]\n  &\\answer{= \\dfrac{224}{729}}\\end{aligned}\n  $$\n\n- \n  - On each round, either Jack wins or John wins. Hence in seven rounds, there are $2^7 = 128$ possible outcomes.\n  - Using the binomial theorem, we have\n\n    $$\n    (1 + y)^7  =  \\sum_{k = 0}^7 \\binom{7}{k}\\hspace{0.05em}y^k \\hspace{0.3em} \\qref{(1)}\n    $$\n\n    Hence, if we substitute $y = 1$ in the equation $(1)$, we get\n\n    $$\n    \\hspace{0.7em} \\answer{128 = \\sum_{k = 0}^7 \\binom{7}{k}}\n    $$\n\n  - The total number of outcomes equals to the sum of the number of ways Jack can win $k$ rounds over $k = 0,1,2,\\dots,7$.\n\n- \n  - The expected amount of money earned by Jack in the game is\n\n    $$\n    \\begin{aligned}\n    \\hspace{0.2em} \\mathrm{E}[\\$ \\text{ earned by Jack}] &= 7\\left[(\\$\\hspace{0.05em}4)\\cdot\\frac{1}{3} + (-\\$\\hspace{0.05em}2)\\cdot\\frac{2}{3}\\right] \\\\[3pt]\n    &\\answer{= \\$\\hspace{0.05em}0.00}\\end{aligned}\n    $$\n\n    The expected amount of money earned by John in the game is\n\n    $$\n    \\begin{aligned}\n    \\mathrm{E}[\\$ \\text{ earned by John}] &= 7\\left[(-\\$\\hspace{0.05em}4)\\cdot\\frac{1}{3} + (\\$\\hspace{0.05em}2)\\cdot\\frac{2}{3}\\right] \\\\[3pt]\n    &\\answer{= \\$\\hspace{0.05em}0.00}\\end{aligned}\n    $$\n\n  - Since no one is expected to earn money in the game, no one is expected to win the game.\n  - Yes, this game is fair because no one is expected to win or lose the~game.\n\n- \n  - The probability that John wins a round is $\\dfrac{2}{3}$.\nHence the probability that John wins five rounds on the first\ngame and two rounds on the second game is\n\n    $$\n    \\left[\\binom{7}{5}\\bigg[\\dfrac{2}{3}\\bigg]^5\\bigg[\\dfrac{1}{3}\\bigg]^2\\right]\\left[\\binom{7}{2}\\bigg[\\dfrac{2}{3}\\bigg]^2\\bigg[\\dfrac{1}{3}\\bigg]^5\\right]  =  \\hspace{0.525em}\\answer{\\binom{7}{5}^2\\bigg[\\dfrac{2}{3}\\bigg]^7\\bigg[\\dfrac{1}{3}\\bigg]^7}\n    $$\n\n  - Similarly as in (d) (i), the probability that John wins a total\nof seven rounds over two games is\n\n    $$\n    \\sum_{k = 0}^7 \\binom{7}{k}^2\\bigg[\\dfrac{2}{3}\\bigg]^7\\bigg[\\dfrac{1}{3}\\bigg]^7 = \\hspace{0.525em}\\answer{\\bigg[\\dfrac{2^7}{3^{14}}\\bigg]\\sum_{k = 0}^7 \\binom{7}{k}^2}\n    $$\n\n  - Equivalently, the probability that John wins $7$ rounds out of\n$14$ is\n\n    $$\n    \\binom{14}{7}\\bigg[\\dfrac{2}{3}\\bigg]^7\\bigg[\\dfrac{1}{3}\\bigg]^7 = \\binom{14}{7}\\bigg[\\dfrac{2^7}{3^{14}}\\bigg] \\hspace{0.75em}\n    $$\n\n    Hence we obtain\n\n    $$\n    \\begin{aligned}\n    \\binom{14}{7}\\bcancel{\\bigg[\\dfrac{2^7}{3^{14}}\\bigg]} &= \\bcancel{\\bigg[\\dfrac{2^7}{3^{14}}\\bigg]}\\sum_{k = 0}^7 \\binom{7}{k}^2 \\\\\n    \\end{aligned}\n    $$\n\n\n    $$\n    \\answer{\\binom{14}{7} = \\sum_{k = 0}^7 \\binom{7}{k}^2} \\hspace{0.15em}\n    $$\n\n\n- \n  - The expected value of $A$ is\n\n    $$\n    \\begin{aligned}\n    \\hspace{3em} \\mathrm{E}[A] &= \\sum_{r=0}^{12} r\\binom{12}{r}\\bigg[\\dfrac{1}{3}\\bigg]^r\\bigg[\\dfrac{2}{3}\\bigg]^{12-r} \\\\[6pt]\n    &=  \\sum_{r=0}^{12} r\\binom{12}{r}\\left[\\dfrac{2^{12-r}}{3^{12}}\\right]\\end{aligned}\n    $$\n\n    Hence\n$\\answer{a = 2}$\nand  $\\answer{b = 3}$\n  - Using the binomial theorem, we have\n\n    $$\n    (1 + y)^{12}  =  \\sum_{k = 0}^{12} \\binom{12}{k}\\hspace{0.05em}y^k \\hspace{1.2em} \\qref{(2)}\n    $$\n\n    Hence, if we differentiate both sides of the equation $(2)$, we\nget\n\n    $$\n    \\begin{aligned}\n    \\dfrac{\\mathrm{d}}{\\mathrm{d}y}\\left[(1 + y)^{12}\\right] &= \\dfrac{\\mathrm{d}}{\\mathrm{d}y}\\left[\\sum_{r=0}^{12} \\binom{12}{r} y^{r}\\right] \\hspace{0.9em} \\\\[6pt]\n    12(1 + y)^{11} &= \\sum_{r=0}^{12} r\\binom{12}{r} y^{r-1} \\qref{(3)}\\end{aligned}\n    $$\n\n    To obtain $\\dfrac{3^{12}}{2^{11}}$ on the left hand side and\n$2^{1-r}$ on the right hand side of\n    the equation $(3)$, we need to substitute $y = \\dfrac{1}{2}$ in\nthis equation.\n\n    $$\n    \\begin{aligned}\n    12\\left(1 + \\dfrac{1}{2}\\right)^{11} &= \\sum_{r=0}^{12} r\\binom{12}{r} \\bigg[\\dfrac{1}{2}\\bigg]^{r-1} \\hspace{0.5em} \\\\[6pt]\n    4\\cdot\\dfrac{3^{12}}{2^{11}} &= \\sum_{r=0}^{12} r\\binom{12}{r} \\big[2^{1-r}\\big] \\qref{(4)}\\end{aligned}\n    $$\n\n    Hence, if we rewrite the equation $(4)$, we obtain\n\n    $$\n    \\begin{aligned}\n    \\hspace{4.5em} 4 &= \\sum_{r=0}^{12} r\\binom{12}{r} \\left[\\dfrac{2^{12-r}}{3^{12}}\\right] \\\\\n    \\end{aligned}\n    $$\n\n\n    $$\n    \\answer{4 = \\mathrm{E}[A]} \\hspace{1.9em}\n    $$\n\n\n',
