      'Consider the equation $\\dfrac{3z}{5-z^{*}}=\\text{i}$, where\n$z=x+\\text{i}y$ and $x$, $y \\in \\mathbb{R}$.\nFind the value of $x$ and the value of $y$.',
    markScheme:
      'We have\n\n$$\n\\begin{aligned}\n\\dfrac{3z}{5-z^{*}}&=\\text{i} \\\\[12pt]\n\\dfrac{3(x+\\text{i}y)}{5-(x-\\text{i}y)}&= \\text{i}\\\\[12pt]\n\\dfrac{3x+3y\\text{i}}{5-x+y\\text{i}}&=\\text{i}\\\\[12pt]\n3x+3y\\text{i}&=\\text{i}(5-x+y\\text{i}) \\\\[12pt]\n3x+3y\\text{i}&=5\\text{i}-x\\text{i}-y\\\\[12pt]\n3x+3y\\text{i}&=-y+(5-x)\\text{i}\\end{aligned}\n$$\n\nComplex numbers can be\nequal only if their real and imaginary parts are equal.\nEquating the real\nparts, we get\n\n$$\n\\begin{aligned}\n3x&=-y \\\\[8pt]\ny&=-3x \\qref{(1)}\\end{aligned}\n$$\n\nEquating the imaginary parts, we get\n\n$$\n\\begin{aligned}\n3y&=5-x \\\\[8pt]\n3(-3x)&=5-x \\hspace{4em} [\\hspace{0.1em}\\text{by equation (1)}\\hspace{0.1em}]\\\\[8pt]\n-9x&=5-x\\\\[8pt]\n&\\hspace{-0.55em}\\answer{x=-\\dfrac{5}{8}}\\\\\n\\end{aligned}\n$$\n\nSubstituting the value of $x$ in equation $(1)$, we get\n\n$$\n\\begin{aligned}\ny&=-3\\left(-\\dfrac{5}{8}\\right)\\\\[12pt]\n&\\hspace{-0.55em}\\answer{y=\\dfrac{15}{8}}\\end{aligned}\n$$\n',
