    content:
      'On an Argand diagram, the complex numbers\n$z_1 = 2 + 2\\sqrt{3}{\\mathrm{\\hspace{0.05em}i}\\mkern 1mu}$,\n$z_2 = 1 - {\\mathrm{\\hspace{0.05em}i}\\mkern 1mu}$ and $z_3 = z_1z_2$ are\nrepresented by the vertices of a triangle.\nThe exact area of the triangle can be expressed in the form\n$p+\\sqrt{q}$. Find the value of $p$ and of $q$.',
    markScheme:
      'We have\n\n$$\n\\begin{aligned}\n\\hspace{1.1em} |z_1| &= \\textstyle \\sqrt{2^2+(2\\sqrt{3})^2} \\\\[6pt]\n&= 4 \\\\[12pt]\n|z_2| &= \\sqrt{1^2+(-1)^2} \\\\[6pt]\n&= \\sqrt{2}\\end{aligned}\n$$\n\nand\n\n$$\n\\begin{aligned}\n\\arg z_1 &= \\tan^{-1}(2\\sqrt{3}/2) \\\\[6pt]\n&= \\ang{60} \\\\[12pt]\n\\arg z_2 &= \\tan^{-1}(-1/1) \\\\[6pt]\n&= -\\ang{45}\\end{aligned}\n$$\n\nHence, using the property of modulus, we get\n\n$$\n\\begin{aligned}\n|z_3| &= |z_1z_2| \\\\[6pt]\n&= |z_1||z_2| \\hspace{2.1em} \\\\[6pt]\n&= 4\\sqrt{2}\\end{aligned}\n$$\n\nand\n\n$$\n\\begin{aligned}\n\\arg z_3 &= \\arg(z_1z_2) \\\\[6pt]\n&= \\arg z_1 + \\arg z_2 \\\\[6pt]\n&= \\ang{15}\\end{aligned}\n$$\n\nIf we sketch the triangle whose vertices represent $z_1$, $z_2$ and\n$z_3$ on an Argand diagram, we have\n![SkillUpp Image](https://assets.revisionvillage.com/public/question/9d725016-9066-4b8c-ac95-c47814030441/images/d6a47e5a-26b2-4956-8144-2fd2e75f4f4d/e1e467a933ff283d4afc5581ecd27d102258be6b.svg)\n\n\nHence the area of the triangle ABC is\n\n$$\n\\begin{aligned}\n\\text{area(A\\^{B}C)} &= \\text{area(A\\^{O}C)} + \\text{area(B\\^{O}C)} - \\text{area(A\\^{O}B)} \\\\[10pt]\n&= \\dfrac{1}{2}(4)(4\\sqrt{2})\\sin \\ang{45} + \\dfrac{1}{2}(\\sqrt{2})(4\\sqrt{2})\\sin \\ang{60} - \\dfrac{1}{2}(4)(\\sqrt{2})\\sin \\left(\\ang{60}+\\ang{45}\\right) \\\\[10pt]\n&= (8\\sqrt{2})\\left(\\dfrac{1}{\\sqrt{2}}\\right) + 4 \\left(\\dfrac{\\sqrt{3}}{2}\\right) - 2\\sqrt{2}\\,\\Big(\\sin \\left(\\ang{60}\\right)\\cos(\\ang{45})+\\cos(\\ang{60})\\sin(\\ang{45}) \\Big)\\\\[8pt]\n&= 8+2\\sqrt{3}-2\\sqrt{2}\\left(\\dfrac{\\sqrt{3}}{2}\\dfrac{1}{\\sqrt{2}}+\\dfrac{1}{2}\\dfrac{1}{\\sqrt{2}}\\right)\\\\[10pt]\n&= 7+\\sqrt{3}\\end{aligned}\n$$\n\nTherefore,\n$\\answer{p=7}$and$\\answer{q=3}$',
    paper: 'PAPER1',
