    content:
      '\n- Solve $2\\sin(x+\\ang{120}) = \\sqrt{3}\\cos(x + \\ang{60})$, for\n$x \\in [0,\\ang{180}]$.  <span class="marks">[5]</span>\n\n- Show that $\\sin \\ang{75} + \\cos \\ang{75} = \\dfrac{\\sqrt{6}}{2}$.\n<span class="marks">[3]</span>\n\n- Let\n$z = \\sin 4\\theta + {\\mathrm{\\hspace{0.05em}i}\\mkern 1mu}(1 - \\cos 4\\theta)$,\nfor $z \\in \\mathbb{C}$, $\\theta \\in [0,\\ang{90}]$.\n  \n  - Find the modulus and argument of $z$ in terms of $\\theta$.\n  - Hence find the fourth roots of $z$ in modulus-argument form.\n<span class="marks">[14]</span>\n\n\n',
    markScheme:
      "\n- Using the compound angle formulas for sine and cosine, we find\n\n  $$\n  \\begin{aligned}\n  2\\sin(x+\\ang{120}) &= \\sqrt{3}\\cos(x + \\ang{60}) \\\\[12pt]\n  2\\hspace{0.05em}(\\sin x \\cos \\ang{120} + \\cos x \\sin \\ang{120}) &= \\sqrt{3}\\hspace{0.05em}(\\cos x \\cos \\ang{60} - \\sin x \\sin \\ang{60}) \\\\[12pt]\n  2\\sin x \\hspace{0.05em}(- \\sin \\ang{30}) + 2\\cos x \\cos \\ang{30} &= \\sqrt{3}\\cos x \\cos \\ang{60} - \\sqrt{3}\\sin x \\sin \\ang{60} \\\\[6pt]\n  2\\sin x \\bigg(\\hspace{-0.3em}-\\dfrac{1}{2}\\bigg) + 2\\cos x\\bigg(\\dfrac{\\sqrt{3}}{2}\\bigg) &= \\sqrt{3}\\cos x \\bigg(\\dfrac{1}{2}\\bigg) - \\sqrt{3}\\sin x \\bigg(\\dfrac{\\sqrt{3}}{2}\\bigg)  \\\\[6pt]\n  -2\\sin x + 2\\sqrt{3}\\cos x &= \\sqrt{3}\\cos x - 3\\sin x  \\\\[12pt]\n  \\sin x &= -\\sqrt{3}\\cos x \\\\[12pt]\n  \\tan x &= -\\sqrt{3} \\\\\n  \\end{aligned}\n  $$\n\n\n  $$\n  \\hspace{1.2em} \\answer{x = \\ang{120}}\n  $$\n\n- Using the compound angle formula for sine, we get\n\n  $$\n  \\begin{aligned}\n  (\\sin \\ang{75} + \\cos \\ang{75})^2 &= (\\sin \\ang{75})^2 + (\\cos \\ang{75})^2 + 2\\sin \\ang{75}\\cos \\ang{75}\\\\[12pt]\n  &= 1 + \\sin \\left(\\ang{75} + \\ang{75}\\right) \\\\[12pt]\n  &= 1 + \\cos \\ang{60} \\\\[7pt]\n  &= 1 + \\dfrac{1}{2} \\\\[4pt]\n  &= \\dfrac{6}{4} \\qref{(1)}\\end{aligned}\n  $$\n\n  Hence, if we take the\nsquare root of both sides of the equality $(1)$, we obtain\n\n  $$\n  \\begin{aligned}\n  \\answer{\\sin \\ang{75} + \\cos \\ang{75} = \\dfrac{\\sqrt{6}}{2}}\\end{aligned}\n  $$\n\n- \n  - The modulus of $z$ is\n\n    $$\n    \\begin{aligned}\n    \\hspace{3em} |z| &= \\left[(\\sin 4\\theta)^2  + (1 - \\cos 4 \\theta)^2\\right]^{\\frac{1}{2}} \\\\[5pt]\n    &= \\left[(\\sin 4\\theta)^2 + (\\cos 4 \\theta)^2 + 1 - 2\\cos 4\\theta\\right]^{\\frac{1}{2}} \\\\[5pt]\n    &= \\left[2 - 2\\cos 4 \\theta\\right]^{\\frac{1}{2}} \\\\[5pt]\n    &= \\left[2\\hspace{0.05em}(1 - \\cos 4\\theta)\\right]^{\\frac{1}{2}} \\\\[5pt]\n    &= \\left[2\\big(1-(1 - 2\\hspace{0.05em}(\\sin 2\\theta)^2\\big)\\right]^{\\frac{1}{2}} \\hspace{2em} [\\text{by double-angle formula}] \\\\[5pt]\n    &= \\left[4\\hspace{0.05em}(\\sin 2\\theta)^2\\right]^{\\frac{1}{2}} \\\\[10pt]\n    &= 2\\hspace{0.05em}|\\hspace{-0.05em}\\sin 2\\theta\\hspace{0.05em}| \\\\[10pt]\n    &\\answer{= 2\\sin 2\\theta} \\hspace{3em} [\\text{since $\\sin 2\\theta \\geq 0$ for $\\theta \\in [0,\\ang{90}]$}]\\end{aligned}\n    $$\n\n    Using the double-angle formulas for sine and cosine, we have\n\n    $$\n    \\begin{aligned}\n    \\tan \\left(\\arg z\\right) &= \\dfrac{1- \\cos 4\\theta}{\\sin 4\\theta} \\hspace{2.4em} \\\\[4pt]\n    &= \\dfrac{1-\\big[1 - 2(\\sin 2\\theta)^2\\big]}{2\\sin 2\\theta\\cos 2\\theta} \\\\[6pt]\n    &= \\dfrac{\\sin 2\\theta}{\\cos 2\\theta} \\\\[10pt]\n    &= \\tan 2\\theta\\end{aligned}\n    $$\n\n    Hence the argument of $z$ is\n$\\answer{\\arg z = 2 \\theta}$\n  - Hence, using part (c) and de Moivre's theorem, we find\n\n    $$\n    \\begin{aligned}\n    \\hspace{3em} z^\\frac{1}{4} &= (2\\sin 2\\theta \\mathop{\\mathrm{cis}}2\\theta)^\\frac{1}{4} \\\\[12pt]\n    &= \\sqrt[4]{2\\sin 2\\theta}\\mathop{\\mathrm{cis}}\\left(\\dfrac{2\\theta + 2k\\pi}{4}\\right) \\\\[6pt]\n    &\\answer{= \\sqrt[4]{2\\sin 2\\theta}\\mathop{\\mathrm{cis}}\\left(\\dfrac{\\theta + k\\pi}{2}\\right)}\\end{aligned}\n    $$\n\n    for $k = 0,1,2,3$.\n\n",
