    type: 'SAQ',
    title: 'Question 32',
    content:
      'Consider the complex numbers $z_1=-1+\\sqrt{3}ai$ and $z_2=\\dfrac{\\sqrt{3}(a-1)}{3a+1}+i$.  Where $a \\in \\mathbb{R}, a\\neq-\\tfrac{1}{3}$.\nAnother complex number is defined such that $z_3=\\dfrac{z_2}{z_1}$.\nLet $\\theta=\\arg({z_3})$, where $-\\pi \\leq \\theta \\leq \\pi$.\n\n- Show that $\\tan{\\theta}$ is constant for $a \\in \\mathbb{R}, a\\neq-\\tfrac{1}{3}$. <span class="marks">[4]</span>\n\n- Hence, find the two possible values of $\\theta$ and the intervals of $a$ for which they will occur.<span class="marks">[3]</span>\n\n',
    markScheme:
      '\n- Begin by dividing the two complex numbers\n\n  $$\n  \\begin{align*}\n  z_3&=\\frac{\\tfrac{\\sqrt{3}(a-1)}{3a+1}+i}{-1+\\sqrt{3}ai}\\\\[3pt]\n  \\end{align*}\n  $$\n\n  Multiply the top and bottom by the complex conjugate of $z_1$, then simplify\n\n  $$\n  \\begin{align*}\n      &=\\frac{\\tfrac{\\sqrt{3}(a-1)}{3a+1}+i}{-1+\\sqrt{3}ai}\\times\\frac{{-1-\\sqrt{3}ai}}{{-1-\\sqrt{3}ai}} \\\\[6pt]\n      &=\\frac{\\tfrac{\\sqrt{3}(a-1)(-1-\\sqrt{3}ai)}{3a+1}+(-1-\\sqrt{3}ai)i}{3a^2+1} \\tag*{\\textbf{A1}}\\\\[3pt]\n  \\end{align*}\n  $$\n\n  Write the numerator as a single fraction and simplify\n\n  $$\n  \\begin{align*}\n      &=\\tfrac{1}{3a^2+1}\\left(\\frac{\\sqrt{3}(a-1)(-1-\\sqrt{3}ai)+(-i+\\sqrt{3}a)(1+3a)}{3a+1}\\right)\\\\[3pt]\n      &=\\tfrac{1}{3a^2+1}\\left(\\frac{\\sqrt{3}(-a-\\sqrt{3}a^2i+1+\\sqrt{3}ai)-i-3ai+\\sqrt{3}a+3\\sqrt{3}a^2}{3a+1}\\right) \\tag*{\\textbf{A1}}\n  \\end{align*}\n  $$\n\n  Cancel out terms.\n\n  $$\n  \\begin{align*}\n  &=\\tfrac{1}{3a^2+1}\\left(\\frac{\\cancel{-\\sqrt{3}a}-3a^2i +\\sqrt{3}+\\cancel{3ai}-i-\\cancel{3ai}+\\cancel{\\sqrt{3}a}+3\\sqrt{3}a^2}{3a+1}\\right)\\\\[3pt]\n  &=\\tfrac{1}{3a^2+1}\\left(\\frac{\\sqrt{3}+3\\sqrt{3}a^2-(3a^2+1)i}{3a+1}\\right)\\\\[3pt]\n  &=\\tfrac{1}{\\cancel{3a^2+1}}\\left(\\frac{\\sqrt{3}\\cancel{(3a^2+1)}-\\cancel{(3a^2+1)i}}{3a+1}\\right)\\\\\n  &=\\tfrac{1}{3a+1}\\left(\\sqrt{3}-i\\right) \\tag*{\\textbf{A1}}\n  \\end{align*}\n  $$\n\n  Hence we can find $\\tan\\theta$ independent of $a$\n\n  $$\n  \\tag*{\\textbf{R1}}\n  $$\n\n\n  $$\n  \\begin{align*}\n      &=-\\frac{1}{\\sqrt{3}}\\\\[3pt]\n  \\end{align*}\n  $$\n\n  Therefore\\hspace{1em}$\\answer{ \\tan{\\theta}\\text{ is constant for a }\\in \\mathbb{R}, a\\neq-\\tfrac{1}{3}}$\n- First we can find the two values of $\\theta$\n\n  $$\n  \\begin{align*}  \n      \\theta&=\\arctan{\\left(-\\frac{1}{\\sqrt{3}}\\right)}\\\\[3pt]\n      &=-\\frac{\\pi}{6},\\,\\frac{5\\pi}{6} \\tag*{\\textbf{A1}}\n  \\end{align*}  \n  $$\n\n  We can now sketch two representations of $z_3=\\frac{1}{3a+1}(\\sqrt{3}-i)$ on Argand diagrams which both have the same value for $\\tan \\theta$.\n\n  $$\n  \\tag*{\\textbf{M1}}\n  $$\n\n  When $\\frac{1}{3a+1}>0$ then $\\theta = -\\dfrac{\\pi}{6}$ and when $\\frac{1}{3a+1}<0$ then $\\theta = \\dfrac{5\\pi}{6}$\n  ![SkillUpp Image](https://assets.revisionvillage.com/public/question/e096ec96-6e1c-4e9d-8c5d-46e07f491b2a/images/1194ed2c-6596-414f-857d-5b89d8fd0861/ans1.png)\n\n\n  We can use a sign diagram (or a sketch) to determine the conditions for the sign of $\\tfrac{1}{3a+1}$.\n  ![SkillUpp Image](https://assets.revisionvillage.com/public/question/e096ec96-6e1c-4e9d-8c5d-46e07f491b2a/images/6171c81d-eaa5-4a08-9737-530f9d0d738f/ans2.png)\n\n\n  Therefore $\\tfrac{1}{3a+1}>0$ when $a>-\\tfrac{1}{3}$ and $\\tfrac{1}{3a+1}<0$ when $a<-\\tfrac{1}{3}$\n  Hence\n\n  $$\n  \\answer{\\theta = -\\tfrac{\\pi}{6} \\text{ for } a>-\\tfrac{1}{3} \\text{ and } \\theta = \\tfrac{5\\pi}{6} \\text{ \n  for } a<-\\tfrac{1}{3}}\\tag*{\\textbf{A1}}\n  $$\n\n',
