    content:
      'Consider the function defined by $f(x) = (2x-6)\\ln(x+3)+x$ for\n$x \\in \\mathbb{R}$, $x>p$.\n\n- Find the value of $p$. <span class="marks">[2]</span>\n\n- Find an expression for $f\'(x)$. <span class="marks">[3]</span>\n\n\nThe graph of $y=f(x)$ has no points of\ninflexion.\n\n- Determine if the graph of $y=f(x)$ is concave down or\nconcave up over its domain. <span class="marks">[3]</span>  \n\nThe function $g$ is defined by $g(x)=3\\ln\\left(\\dfrac{1}{x+3}\\right)+x$,\nfor $x\\in \\mathbb{R}$, $x>-3$.\n\n- Find an expression for $g\'(x)$. <span class="marks">[4]</span>\n\n- Find the horizontal and vertical asymptotes of\n$g\'(x)$.<span class="marks">[2]</span>\n\n- Find the exact value of the minimum of $y=g(x)$.<span class="marks">[3]</span>\n\n- Solve $f(x)<g(x)$ for $x\\in \\mathbb{R}$, $x>-3$.<span class="marks">[5]</span>\n\n',
    markScheme:
      "\n- Due to the natural log term, $x+3>0$. Therefore\n$\\answer{ p=-3}$\n- Differentiating $f$ with respect to $x$, we obtain\n\n  $$\n  \\begin{aligned}\n  f'(x) &= \\dfrac{\\mathrm{d}}{\\mathrm{d}x}\\big[(2x-6)\\ln(x+3)+x\\big] \\\\[10pt]\n  & \\answer{=\\dfrac{2x-6}{x+3}+2\\ln(x+3)+1} \\end{aligned}\n  $$\n\n- Differentiating $f'$ with respect to $x$, we obtain\n\n  $$\n  \\begin{aligned}\n  f''(x) &= \\dfrac{\\mathrm{d}}{\\mathrm{d}x}\\left[\\dfrac{2x-6}{x+3}+2\\ln(x+3)+1\\right] \\\\[12pt]\n  &= \\dfrac{(x+3)(2)-(2x-6)}{\\left(x+3\\right)^2} + \\dfrac{2}{x+3} \\\\[12pt]\n  &= \\dfrac{2x+18}{(x+3)^2}\\end{aligned}\n  $$\n\n  Hence, over $x>-3$, we have $f''(x)>0$. Therefore,\n$\\answer{f \\text{ is concave up}}$\n- Differentiating $g$ with respect to $x$, we obtain\n\n  $$\n  \\begin{aligned}\n  g'(x) &= \\dfrac{\\mathrm{d}}{\\mathrm{d}x}\\left[3\\ln\\left(\\dfrac{1}{x+3}\\right)+x\\right] \\\\[12pt]\n  &=3(x+3)\\left(-\\dfrac{1}{(x+3)^2}\\right)+1  \\\\[8pt]\n  & =\\dfrac{-3}{x+3}+1 \\\\[10pt] \n  & \\answer{=\\dfrac{x}{x+3}} \\end{aligned}\n  $$\n\n- The denominator of $g'$ is zero when $x=-3$.\nHence,\n$\\answer{\\text{the line \\(x=-3\\) is a vertical asymptote of the graph of \\(y=g'(x)\\)}}$\nIf we take the limit as $x$ tends to $\\infty$, we have\n\n  $$\n  \\begin{aligned}\n  \\lim_{x\\to \\infty} g'(x) &= \\lim_{x\\to \\infty} \\dfrac{x}{x+3}%\\cdot \\dfrac{\\dfrac{1}{x}}{\\dfrac{1}{x}}\n  \\\\[8pt]\n  & = \\lim_{x\\to \\infty} \\dfrac{1}{1+\\dfrac{3}{x}\\rule[-2mm]{0pt}{7.2mm}} \\\\[6pt]\n  & = 1 \\\\\n  \\end{aligned}\n  $$\n\n  Hence,\n$\\answer{\\text{the line \\(y=1\\) is a horizontal asymptote of the graph of \\(y=g'(x)\\)}}$\n- From part (d) we obtain a stationary point at $x=0$.\nThe second derivative of $g$ is\n\n  $$\n  \\begin{aligned}\n  g''(x) &= \\dfrac{\\mathrm{d}}{\\mathrm{d}x} \\left[\\dfrac{x}{x+3}\\right] \\\\[12pt]\n  &= \\dfrac{3}{(x+3)^2}\\end{aligned}\n  $$\n\n  Hence, $g''(x)>0$ which implies that at $x=0$ the function $g$\nreaches its minimum. Therefore, the minimum value of $g$ is\n\n  $$\n  \\begin{aligned}\n  g(0) &= 3\\ln\\left(\\dfrac{1}{3}\\right)+0 \\\\[12pt]\n  &\\answer{= -3\\ln(3)} \\end{aligned}\n  $$\n\n- Using logarithm properties, we get\n\n  $$\n  \\begin{aligned}\n  f(x) &< g(x) \\\\[12pt]\n  (2x-6)\\ln(x+3) + x &< 3\\ln\\left(\\dfrac{1}{x+3}\\right) + x \\\\[12pt]\n  (2x-6)\\ln(x+3) &< -3\\ln(x+3) \\\\[15pt]\n  (2x-3)\\ln(x+3) &< 0\\end{aligned}\n  $$\n\n  Thus, we have two options\n\n  $$\n  \\begin{aligned}\n  \\left[2x-3<0\\enskip\\&\\enskip \\ln(x+3)>0\\right] &\\text{  or  } \\left[2x-3>0 \\enskip\\&\\enskip \\ln(x+3)<0\\right] \\\\[12pt]\n  \\left[x<1.5\\enskip\\&\\enskip\\ln(x+3)>0\\right]&\\text{ or } \\left[x>1.5\\enskip\\&\\enskip \\ln(x+3)<0\\right] \\\\[12pt]\n  x < 1.5\\enskip & \\&\\enskip 1<x+3 \\hspace{2em}[\\text{since }\\ln(x+3)>0\\text{ for }x>1.5]\\\\[8pt]\n  -2 <& \\hspace{0.1em}x < 1.5 \\\\\n  \\end{aligned}\n  $$\n\n  Therefore,\n$f(x)<g(x)$ over $\\answer{-2 <  x < 1.5}$\n",
