      'Consider the function $f(x)=\\dfrac{e^x-e^{-x}}{2}$, $x\\in \\mathbb{R}$.\n\n- Show that $f$ is an odd function. <span class="marks">[2]</span>  \n\nNow, consider the function $g$ given by $g(x) = \\dfrac{x^4+2}{2x}$ , $x\\in \\mathbb{R}, x \\neq 0$.\n\n- By considering the graph of $y=f(x)-g(x)$, solve $f(x)>g(x)$ for $x\\in \\mathbb{R}$. <span class="marks">[4]</span>  \n',
    markScheme:
      '\n- Evaluating $f(-x)$, we get\n\n  $$\n  \\begin{align*}\n  f(-x) &= \\dfrac{e^{-x}-e^{-(-x)}}{2} \\\\[10pt]\n  &= \\dfrac{e^{-x}-e^{x}}{2} \\\\[10pt]\n  &= -\\dfrac{e^{x}-e^{-x}}{2} \\\\[10pt]\n  &= -f(x) \\\\[-8pt]\n  \\end{align*}\n  $$\n\n  $\\answer{\\text{Therefore, $f(x)$ is an odd function}}$\n- If $f(x)-g(x)>0$, then $f(x)>g(x)$. Using G.D.C., we get\n  ![SkillUpp Image](https://assets.revisionvillage.com/public/question/cf76b687-c4cf-4f02-a51c-0d0d8c929218/images/0ae01be6-8c62-4dff-b5d4-bdc1c895874f/AA930a.PNG)\n\n\n  We see that $f(x)-g(x)>0$ for $-4.55 < x < 0$ and $x > 4.55$.\n  Therefore $f(x)>g(x)$ over the intervals\r\n$\\answer{-4.55 < x < 0 \\text{ and } x > 4.55}$\n',
