      'Let $f(x) = \\dfrac{4-ax}{5x - 2}$.\n\n- Write down the equation of the vertical asymptote of the graph of $y = f(x)$.<span class="marks">[1]</span>  \n\nThe line $y = -1.4$ is a horizontal asymptote to the graph of $y = f(x)$.\n\n- Find the value of $a$.<span class="marks">[2]</span>\n\n- The line $y = x - c$, where $c \\in \\mathbb{R}^+$, intersects the graph of $y = \\big|f(x)\\big|$ at exactly one point. Find the possible values of $c$. <span class="marks">[4]</span>\n\n',
    markScheme:
      '\n- Solving the equation $5x-2=0$, we have $\\tcbhighmath{x = \\dfrac{2}{5}}$\n- The horizontal asymptote will be equal to $\\displaystyle\\lim_{x \\to \\pm \\infty}f(x)$. We have\n\n  $$\n  \\begin{align*}\n  \\displaystyle\\lim_{x \\to \\pm \\infty}f(x) &= \\displaystyle\\lim_{x \\to \\pm \\infty}\\dfrac{4-ax}{5x-2} \\\\[8pt]\n  -1.4 &= -\\dfrac{a}{5} \\\\[8pt]\n  &\\hspace{-0.5em}\\tcbhighmath{a=7}\n  \\end{align*}\n  $$\n\n- If we draw the graph of $y = |f(x)|$ [by using G.D.C.], we have\n  ![SkillUpp Image](https://assets.revisionvillage.com/public/question/d38234a3-2406-4a17-ad72-c2dccf3aebd1/images/423ecaf7-2110-4ebe-8d00-cb3ef860ab02/aa1027a.PNG)\n\n\n  A line of the form $y = x - c$ where $c \\in \\mathbb{R}^+$ has a gradient of $m=1$ and a $y$-intercept that is less than zero. The following diagram shows the graph of $y=x$, which represents an absolute upper limit for the $y$-intercept.\n  ![SkillUpp Image](https://assets.revisionvillage.com/public/question/d38234a3-2406-4a17-ad72-c2dccf3aebd1/images/66fa47d7-6be3-4bd7-bfc8-104af16f2d66/aa1027b.PNG)\n\n\n  The line $y=x$ intersects the graph of $y = \\big|f(x)\\big|$ at three points.\n  The following diagram shows the graph of $y=x-0.571$, which passes through the point A$(0.571,0)$ and has a $y$-intercept of $-0.571$.\n  ![SkillUpp Image](https://assets.revisionvillage.com/public/question/d38234a3-2406-4a17-ad72-c2dccf3aebd1/images/47bdebc2-8242-44ff-8e71-2793f3857f00/aa1027c.PNG)\n\n\n  The line $y=x-0.571$ intersects the graph of $y = \\big|f(x)\\big|$ at two points. Any line of gradient $m=1$ and $y$-intercept of less than $-0.571$ will intersect the graph of $y = \\big|f(x)\\big|$ exactly once.\n  Therefore, $\\tcbhighmath{c > 0.571}$\n',
