    content:
      '\n- Sketch the curve $y = -\\left|\\dfrac{5}{x-2}\\right|$ and line\n$y = -x - 4$ on the same axes,\n  clearly indicating any $x$ and $y$ intercepts and any asymptotes.\n<span class="marks">[3]</span>\n\n- Find the exact solutions to the equation $x + 4 = \\dfrac{5}{|x-2|}$.\n<span class="marks">[5]</span>\n\n',
    markScheme:
      '\n- Let $f(x) = -\\left|\\dfrac{5}{x-2}\\right|$ where $x \\in \\mathbb{R}$,\n$x \\neq 2$.\n  Since $f(x) < 0$ for all $x \\in \\mathbb{R}$, $x \\neq 2$, the curve\n$y = f(x)$ has no $x$-intercepts.\n  Evaluating $y = f(x)$ for $x = 0$, we obtain\n\n  $$\n  \\begin{aligned}\n  \\hspace{3em} y &= f(0) \\\\[12pt]\n  &= -\\left|-\\dfrac{5}{2}\\right| \\\\[6pt]\n  &= -\\dfrac{5}{2}\\end{aligned}\n  $$\n\n  Hence the point A$(0,-5/2)$ is the\n$y$-intercept of the curve $y = f(x)$.\n  We have\n\n  $$\n  \\lim_{x \\rightarrow\\pm\\infty} f(x) = 0 \\hspace{3.9em}\n  $$\n\n  Hence the $x$-axis is a horizontal asymptote of the curve\n$y = f(x)$.\n  The denominator of $f$ is zero when $x = 2$. Hence the line $x = 2$\nis a vertical asymptote of the curve $y = f(x)$.\n  The $x$ and $y$ intercepts of the line $y = -4-x$ are B$(-4,0)$ and\nC$(0,-4)$.\n  If we sketch the curve $y = f(x)$ and line $y = -x - 4$ on the same\naxes, we have\n  ![SkillUpp Image](https://assets.revisionvillage.com/public/question/3ce10e6d-6009-49da-a002-42ae1d773968/images/2248acaa-10a6-4043-b8a6-84823cf01ad6/38ce371d4e9621963b29074adf6413c8b9f71c7c.svg)\n\n\n- If we solve the equation $x + 4 = \\dfrac{5}{|x-2|}$ for $x < 2$, we\nfind\n\n  $$\n  \\begin{aligned}\n  x + 4 &= -\\dfrac{5}{x-2} \\hspace{3em} [\\text{since $x - 2 < 0$}] \\\\[9pt]\n  \\hspace{7.7em} (x+4)(x-2) &= -5 \\\\[12pt]\n  x^2 + 2x - 8 &= -5 \\\\[12pt]\n  x^2 + 2x - 3 &= 0 \\\\[13pt]\n  (x + 3)(x - 1) &= 0 \\\\[13pt]\n  x &= -3,\\hspace{0.25em} 1\\end{aligned}\n  $$\n\n  If we simplify the equation\n$x + 4 = \\dfrac{5}{|x-2|}$ for $x > 2$, we have\n\n  $$\n  \\begin{aligned}\n  x + 4 &= \\dfrac{5}{x-2} \\hspace{3em} [\\text{since $x - 2 > 0$}] \\\\[9pt]\n  \\hspace{10em} (x+4)(x-2) &= 5 \\\\[13pt]\n  x^2 + 2x - 8 &= 5 \\\\[13pt]\n  x^2 + 2x - 13 &= 0\\end{aligned}\n  $$\n\n  Hence, using the quadratic\nformula, we find\n\n  $$\n  \\begin{aligned}\n  \\hspace{12em} x &= \\dfrac{-2+\\sqrt{2^2-4(1)(-13)}}{2} \\hspace{3em} [\\text{since $x > 2$}] \\\\[6pt]\n  &= \\dfrac{-2+2\\sqrt{14}}{2} \\\\[12pt]\n  &= -1 + \\sqrt{14} \\\\\n  \\end{aligned}\n  $$\n\n  Hence the\nexact solutions to the equation $\\text{\\(x + 4 = \\dfrac{5}{|x-2|}\\)}$ are  $\\answer{-3,\\hspace{0.25em}1,\\hspace{0.25em}\\textstyle -1 + \\sqrt{14}}$\n',
