    content:
      'Let $f(x) = ax^3 + bx^2 + cx  +  d$, for $x \\in \\mathbb{R}$, where\n$a,b,c,d \\in \\mathbb{Q}$. The diagram below shows part of the graph of\n$y = f(x)$.\n![SkillUpp Image](https://assets.revisionvillage.com/public/question/d78a10f2-621e-426c-91f2-9dea87dbacc5/images/89842500-91d4-4b78-a494-6ce2510b4acf/f2e9d58912ae2f10d7fdf9d12ee3b7594c2c45fb.svg)\n\n\n\n- Using the information shown in the diagram, find the values of $a$,\n$b$, $c$ and $d$.<span class="marks">[4]</span>\n\n- Let $g(x) = -\\dfrac{3}{4}f(-2x+1)$.\n  \n  - Find the coordinates of the points where the graph of $y = g(x)$\nintercepts the $x$-axis.\n  - Find the $y$-intercept of the graph of $y = g(x)$. <span class="marks">[3]</span>\n\n\n',
    markScheme:
      '\n- From the diagram, we see that the roots of the polynomial equation\n$f(x) = 0$ are $-3$, $-1$ and $3$.\n  Hence, using the factor theorem, we have\n\n  $$\n  \\begin{aligned}\n  f(x) &= a(x-3)(x+1)(x+3) \\\\[6pt]\n  &= a(x^2-9)(x+1) \\\\[6pt]\n  &= a(x^3 + x^2 - 9x - 9) \\qref{(1)}\\end{aligned}\n  $$\n\n  If we substitute\n$x = 0$ in the expression $(1)$, we get\n\n  $$\n  \\begin{aligned}\n  \\hspace{2.6em} f(0) &= a(0^3 + 0^2 - 9(0) - 9) \\\\[12pt]\n  -3 &= -9a \\hspace{3em} [\\text{since $f(0) = -3$}] \\\\[6pt]\n  a &= \\dfrac{1}{3}\\end{aligned}\n  $$\n\n  If we substitute $a = 1/3$ in the\nexpression $(1)$, we obtain\n\n  $$\n  \\begin{aligned}\n  f(x) &= \\dfrac{1}{3}(x^3 + x^2 - 9x - 9) \\\\[6pt]\n  &= \\dfrac{1}{3}x^3 + \\dfrac{1}{3}x^2 - 3x - 3 \\hspace{1.1em} \\\\\n  \\end{aligned}\n  $$\n\n  Hence we find\n$\\answer{a = b = \\dfrac{1}{3}}$\nand  $\\answer{c = d = -3}$\n- \n  - Solving the equation $g(x) = 0$ for $x$, we find\n\n    $$\n    \\begin{aligned}\n    -\\dfrac{3}{4}f(-2x + 1) &= 0 \\\\[6pt]\n    f(-2x + 1) &= 0 \\\\[12pt]\n    -2x + 1 &= -3,\\hspace{0.25em} -1,\\hspace{0.25em} 3 \\hspace{4em} \\\\[12pt]\n    -2x &= -4,\\hspace{0.25em} -2,\\hspace{0.25em} 2 \\\\[12pt]\n    x &= -1,\\hspace{0.25em}1,\\hspace{0.25em}2\\end{aligned}\n    $$\n\n    Hence\nthe coordinates of the $x$-intercepts of the graph of $y = g(x)$\nare\n\n    $$\n    \\begin{aligned}\n    \\answer{(-1,0),\\hspace{0.25em}(1,0),\\hspace{0.25em}(2,0)}\\end{aligned}\n    $$\n\n  - Evaluating $y=g(x)$ for $x = 0$, we find\n\n    $$\n    \\begin{aligned}\n    \\hspace{10.9em} y &= g(0) \\\\[10pt]\n    &= -\\dfrac{3}{4}f(2(0)+1) \\\\[6pt]\n    &= -\\dfrac{3}{4}f(1) \\\\[6pt]\n    &= -\\dfrac{3}{4}\\hspace{-0.2em}\\left[\\dfrac{1}{3}(1)^3 + \\dfrac{1}{3}(1)^2 - 3(1) - 3\\right] \\\\[4pt]\n    &=-\\dfrac{3}{4}\\hspace{-0.2em}\\left[-\\dfrac{16}{3}\\right] \\\\[10pt]\n    &= 4\\end{aligned}\n    $$\n\n    Hence the $y$-intercept of the graph of\n$y = g(x)$ is\n$\\answer{\\mathrm{P}(0,4)}$\n\n',
