    content:
      'Consider the family of polynomials of the form $P(x)=ax^3+bx^2+cx+d$ where coefficients $a$, $b$, $c$ and $d$ belong to the set $\\{2,6,8,24\\}$.\n\n- Find the number of possible polynomials if\n  \n  - each coefficient value can be repeated;\n  - each coefficient must be different.<span class="marks">[4]</span>\n\n\n\nConsider the case where $P(x)$ has $x+3$ as a factor, two purely imaginary roots, and all the coefficients are different.\n\n- \n  - By considering the sum of the roots, find the two possible combinations for coefficients $a$ and $b$.\n  - Show that there is only one way to assign the values $a$, $b$, $c$, and $d$ if $P(0)=24$.<span class="marks">[7]</span>\n\n\n\nNow, consider the polynomial with the coefficients found in part (b) (ii).\n\n- \n  - Express $P(x)$ as a product of one linear and one quadratic factor.\n  - Determine the three roots of $P(x)$.<span class="marks">[7]</span>\n\n\n',
    markScheme:
      '\n- Let $X$ be the total number of polynomials.\n  \n  - Given that each coefficient value can be repeated, we have\n\n    $$\n    \\begin{align*}\n    X&=4 \\times 4 \\times 4 \\times 4\\\\[6pt]\n    &=4^4\\\\[6pt]\n    &=256.\n    \\end{align*}\n    $$\n\n    Therefore, there are $\\tcbhighmath{256}$ possible polynomials if the coefficients can be repeated.\n  - Given that each coefficient must be different, we have\n\n    $$\n    \\begin{align*}\n    X&=4!\\\\[6pt]\n    &=4 \\times 3 \\times 2 \\times 1\\\\[6pt]\n    &=24.\n    \\end{align*}\n    $$\n\n    Therefore, there are $\\tcbhighmath{24}$ possible polynomials if each coefficient must be different.\n\n- \n  - Let the roots be $x_1, x_2$ and $x_3$. Given that $x+3$ is a factor, $x_1=-3$ is a root. Complex roots occur in conjugate pairs, therefore if the other two roots are imaginary, we have $x_2 = \\alpha \\mathrm{i}$ and $x_3 = -\\alpha \\mathrm{i}$, where $\\alpha \\in \\mathbb{R}$. Hence, the sum of the roots is given by\n\n    $$\n    \\begin{align*}\n    x_1 + x_2 + x_3 &= -3 + \\alpha \\mathrm{i} - \\alpha \\mathrm{i} \\\\[6pt]\n    &= -3\n    \\end{align*}\n    $$\n\n    Using the formula for the sum of the roots, we have\n\n    $$\n    \\begin{align*}\n    x_1 + x_2 + x_3 &= -\\dfrac{b}{a} \\\\[6pt]\n    -3 &= -\\dfrac{b}{a} \\\\[6pt]\n    3a &= b\n    \\end{align*}\n    $$\n\n    We have that $a$ and $b$ belong to the set $\\{2,6,8,24\\}$ and $3a=b$. Therefore,\n    $\\tcbhighmath{\\text{The two possible combinations are $a=2,\\,b=6$ and $a=8,\\,b=24$.}}$\n  - If $P(0)=24$, we have\n\n    $$\n    \\begin{align*}\n    P(0) &= a(0)^3 + b(0)^2 + c(0) + d \\\\[6pt]\n    24 &= d\n    \\end{align*}\n    $$\n\n    The coefficients must all be different. If $d=24$, $b \\neq 24$, so we have from part (b)(i) that $a=2$ and $b=6$. Therefore $c=8$.\n    $\\tcbhighmath{\\text{If $P(0)=24$, we must have $a=2,\\,b=6,\\,c=8$ and $d=24$.}}$\n\n- \n  - Our polynomial is $P(x) = 2x^3 + 6x^2 + 8x + 24$. Given that $x+3$ is a factor, we have\n\n    $$\n    \\begin{align*}\n    2x^3 + 6x^2 + 8x + 24 &= (x+3)(2x^2 + ex + 8) \\\\[6pt]\n    &= 2x^3 +ex^2 + 8x + 6x^2 +3ex + 24 \\\\[6pt]\n    2x^3 + 6x^2 + 8x + 24 &= 2x^3 + (e+6)x^2 + (8+3e)x +24\n    \\end{align*}\n    $$\n\n    Equating the coefficients of $x^2$ and $x$ on the LHS and RHS, we have\n\n    $$\n    \\begin{align*}\n    6 &= e + 6 \\\\[6pt]\n    8 &= 8 + 3e\n    \\end{align*}\n    $$\n\n    We must have $e=0$. Therefore\n\n    $$\n    \\begin{align*}\n    P(x) &= (x+3)(2x^2 + 8) \\\\[8pt]\n    &\\hspace{-2.1em}\\tcbhighmath{P(x) = 2(x+3)(x^2 + 4)}\n    \\end{align*}\n    $$\n\n  - We have from part (b)(i) that $x_1=-3$. To find the other two roots, we solve $x^2+4=0$:\n\n    $$\n    \\begin{align*}\n    x^2+4&=0 \\\\[6pt]\n    x^2 &= -4 \\\\[6pt]\n    x &= \\pm \\sqrt{-4} \\\\[6pt]\n    x &= \\pm 2\\mathrm{i}\n    \\end{align*}\n    $$\n\n    $\\boxed{\\text{The roots of } P(x) \\text{ are } x_1=-3,\\, x_2=-2\\mathrm{i}, \\text{ and } x_3=2\\mathrm{i}.}$\n\n',
