    content:
      'This question asks you to investigate some properties of cubic functions and their tangents.\nConsider the cubic function $q(x)=x^3-6x^2-x+30$.\n\n- \n  - Show that $x=5$ is a root of $q(x)=0$.\n  - Hence, express $q(x)$ as a product of linear factors.\n  - Find the equation of the tangent to $y=q(x)$ at $x=4$.\n  - Sketch $y=q(x)$ and the tangent at $x=4$ on the same set of axes. <span class="marks">[9]</span>\n\n\n\nConsider the cubic function $f(x)=ax^3+bx^2+cx+d, \\, a\\neq 0,$ and the line $L(x)=mx+1$,\nwith the point $(x_\\ast, f(x_\\ast))$ being a point of inflection on $f(x)$.\nLet $x_1,x_2,x_3$ be the roots of the equation $f(x)-L(x)=0.$\n\n- \n  - Show that the sum of the roots is a constant which is independent of the choice of line $L$.\n  - Show that $y=f(x)$ has an inflection point at $x_\\ast=\\dfrac{x_1+x_2+x_3}{3}.$ <span class="marks">[5]</span>\n\n\n\nSuppose $y=L(x)$ is a tangent to $y=f(x)$ at the point $x=x_1$.\n\n- \n  - Show that $f\'(x)-L\'(x)=3a(x-x_1)(x-\\beta)$ for some $\\beta$.\n  - Hence show that $f(x)-L(x)=\\dfrac{a}{2}(x-x_1)^2(2x+x_1-3\\beta)$.\n  - Assuming it exists, find the $x$-coordinate of the other point of intersection between the cubic and the line, in terms of $x_1$ and $x_\\ast$.\n  - Sketch the functions $f(x)$ and $L(x)$ on the same axes identifying the $x$-coordinate of the points of intersection and inflection.\n  - In the case that $L(x)=0$, interpret the result in (c)(iii) in terms of the graph of the cubic function and its $x$-intercepts. <span class="marks">[13]</span>\n\n\n',
    markScheme:
      "\n- \n  - Evaluating at $x=5$, we get\n\n    $$\n    \\begin{align*}\n        q(5)&=5^3-6(5)^2-(5)+30 \\tag*{\\textbf{M1}}\t\\\\[12pt]\n        &=125-150-5+30\\\\[12pt]\n        &=0 \\tag*{\\textbf{A1}}\t\\\\[-10pt]\n    \\end{align*}\n    $$\n\n\n    $$\n    \\begin{align*}\n    \\answer{\\text{Therefore $x=5$ is a root of } q(x)=0} \n    \\end{align*}\n    $$\n\n  - If we divide $x^3 - 6x^2 - x + 30$ by $x-5$, we have\n\n    $$\n    \\begin{align*}\n    \\tag*{\\textbf{M1}}\n    \\end{align*}\n    $$\n\n    ![SkillUpp Image](https://assets.revisionvillage.com/public/question/e0ecd473-2a75-43b3-8f03-76edd5b41d87/images/3733d937-ec3e-42f3-9446-dadfee5b62c2/alg_div.png)\n\n\n    Hence we get\n\n    $$\n    \\begin{align*}\n        q(x)&=(x-5)(x^2-x-6)\\\\[12pt]\n        &\\hspace{0.275em}\\answer{= (x-5)(x-3)(x+2)} \\tag*{\\textbf{A1}}\n    \\end{align*}\n    $$\n\n  - Taking the derivative of $q$, we obtain\n\n    $$\n    \\begin{align*}\n        q'(x) &= \\left(x^3-6x^2-x+30\\right)' \\tag*{\\textbf{M1}}\\\\[12pt]\n        &= 3x^2-12x-1\\\\[-11pt]\n    \\end{align*}\n    $$\n\n    Hence, the gradient of the tangent line at $x=4$ is\n\n    $$\n    \\begin{align*}\n        q'(4) &= 3(4)^2-12(4)-1\\\\[12pt]\n        &= -1 \\\\[-11pt]\n    \\end{align*}\n    $$\n\n    Also, the line passes through the point with $x=4$ and $y$ coordinate\n\n    $$\n    \\begin{align*}\n        y &= q(4) \\\\[12pt]\n        &= 4^3-6(4)-(4)+30\\\\[12pt]\n        &= -6 \\tag*{\\textbf{A1}}\\\\[-11pt]\n    \\end{align*}\n    $$\n\n    Therefore the equation of the tangent line is\n\n    $$\n    \\begin{align*}\n        y-(-6) &= -(x-4)\\\\[12pt]\n        y+6 &= -x+4 \\\\[12pt]\n        &\\hspace{-0.5em}\\answer{y = -x-2} \\tag*{\\textbf{A1}}\n    \\end{align*}\n    $$\n\n  - \n    - \n\n    ![SkillUpp Image](https://assets.revisionvillage.com/public/question/e0ecd473-2a75-43b3-8f03-76edd5b41d87/images/49419268-112f-4782-b0b5-84a26df9a3ef/da5cfe7af83ea56b6e036c41f1e6bae57f0ce157.svg)\n\n\n    Cubic and line correct shape A1\nCorrect intersection points A1\n\n- \n  - Substituting the expressions for $f(x)$ and $L(x)$ into $f(x)-L(x)=0$, we obtain\n\n    $$\n    \\begin{align*}\n        ax^3+bx^2+cx+d-(mx+1) &= 0 \\tag*{\\textbf{M1}}\\\\[12pt]\n        ax^3+bx^2+(c-m)x+d-1 &= 0 \\\\[-12pt]\n    \\end{align*}\n    $$\n\n    Using the formula for the sum of the roots of a polynomial, we get\n\n    $$\n    \\begin{align*}\n        x_1+x_2+x_3 = -\\dfrac{b}{a} \\tag*{\\textbf{A1}}\n    \\end{align*}\n    $$\n\n    the coefficients $a$ and $b$ are independent of the line $L$.\n  - Taking the first and second derivatives of $f$ with respect to $x$, we get\n\n    $$\n    \\begin{align*}\n    f'(x)&=3ax^2+2bx+c\\\\[12pt]\n    f''(x)&=6ax+2b \\tag*{\\textbf{A1}}\\\\[-12pt]\n    \\end{align*}\n    $$\n\n    Solving for the inflection point, we get\n\n    $$\n    \\begin{align*}\n    f''(x)&=0 \\tag*{\\textbf{M1}}\\\\[12pt]\n    6ax+2b&=0\\\\[12pt]\n    x&=-\\dfrac{2b}{6a}\\\\[12pt]\n    &=\\dfrac{1}{3}\\left(-\\dfrac{b}{a}\\right) \\tag*{\\textbf{A1}}\\\\[12pt]\n    &\\hspace{0.275em}\\answer{= \\dfrac{x_1+x_2+x_3}{3}}\n    \\end{align*}\n    $$\n\n\n- \n  - If the line is a tangent to the cubic at $x=x_1,$ then\n\n    $$\n    \\begin{align*}\n        f(x_1)&=L(x_1) \\\\[12pt]\n        f'(x_1)&=L'(x_1)\\\\[12pt]\n        f'(x_1)-L'(x_1)&=0 \\tag*{\\textbf{M1}}\\\\[-10pt]\n    \\end{align*}\n    $$\n\n    So, $f'(x)-L'(x)$ has a root at $x=x_1$ hence $(x-x_1)$ is a factor.\n\n    $$\n    \\begin{align*}\n    \\tag*{\\textbf{A1}}\n    \\end{align*}\n    $$\n\n    Now, differentiate $f(x)-L(x)$\n\n    $$\n    \\begin{align*}\n    f(x)-L(x)&=ax^3+bx^2+(c-m)x+(d-1)\\\\[12pt]\n    f'(x)-L'(x)&=3ax^2+2bx+(c-m) \\tag*{\\textbf{A1}}\n    \\end{align*}\n    $$\n\n    This quadratic function can be factorised as we know that $(x-x_1)$ is a factor of $f'(x)-L'(x)$.\n\n    $$\n    \\begin{align*}\n    \\tag*{\\textbf{R1}}\n    \\end{align*}\n    $$\n\n    Hence\n\n    $$\n    \\begin{align*}\n        &\\hspace{0.275em}\\tcbhighmath{f'(x)-L'(x)=3a(x-x_1)(x-\\beta) \\text{ for some }\\beta}\\\\[-9pt]\n    \\end{align*}\n    $$\n\n  - Integrating $f(x)-L(x)$ with respect to $x$, we get\n\n    $$\n    \\begin{align*}\n        \\int 3a(x-x_1)(x-\\beta) \\,\\mathrm{d}x\n        &=3a\\int (x-x_1)(x-\\beta) \\,\\mathrm{d}x \\tag*{\\textbf{M1}}\\\\[12pt]\n        &=3a\\left[\\dfrac{1}{2}(x-x_1)^2(x-\\beta)-\\int \\dfrac{1}{2}(x-x_1)^2 \\,\\mathrm{d}x\\right]\\\\[12pt]\n        &=\\dfrac{3a}{2}(x-x_1)^2(x-\\beta)-\\dfrac{a}{2}(x-x_1)^3+C \\tag*{\\textbf{A1}}\\\\[12pt]\n    \\end{align*}\n    $$\n\n    But using that $f(x)-L(x)=0$, we get that $C=0$. Therefore,\n\n    $$\n    \\begin{align*}\n        f(x)-L(x)&=\\dfrac{3a}{2}(x-x_1)^2(x-\\beta)-\\dfrac{a}{2}(x-x_1)^3 \\tag*{\\textbf{A1}}\\\\[12pt]\n        &=\\dfrac{a}{2}(x-x_1)^2(3x-3\\beta-x+x_1)\\\\[12pt]\n        &\\hspace{0.275em}\\answer{= \\dfrac{a}{2}(x-x_1)^2(2x+x_1-3\\beta)}\n    \\end{align*}\n    $$\n\n  - Let the other intersection point occur at $x=x_3$. Hence, we get\n\n    $$\n    \\begin{align*}\n        f(x)-L(x)& =a(x-x_1)^2(x-x_3) \\tag*{\\textbf{M1}}\\\\[12pt]\n    \\end{align*}\n    $$\n\n    using (b)(ii) $x_\\ast$ can be written as\n\n    $$\n    \\begin{align*}\n        x_1+x_1+x_3 &= 3x_\\ast \\\\[6pt]\n        &\\hspace{0.275em}\\tcbhighmath{x_3=3x_\\ast - 2x_1}  \\tag*{\\textbf{A1}}\n    \\end{align*}\n    $$\n\n    \n    - Using the G.D.C.\n      ![SkillUpp Image](https://assets.revisionvillage.com/public/question/e0ecd473-2a75-43b3-8f03-76edd5b41d87/images/98eb0a64-1852-4333-8ab0-9f8155b14d2e/final_graph.png)\n\n\n      2 intersection points A1\nCorrect position of $x_3, x_\\ast$ and $x_1$ A1\n    - \n      $$\n      \\begin{align*}\n          \\answer{\\text{If $L(x)=0$, the $x$-axis is the tangent line and so the graph of the function touches the $x$ axis at $x=x_1$ and crosses the $x$-axis at $x_3=3x_\\ast - 2x_1$.}}\n      \\end{align*}\n      $$\n\n      Reference to where $f(x)$ touches the $x$ axis A1\nReference to where $f(x)$ crosses the $x$ axis A1\n\n\n",
