    title: 'Question 19',
    content:
      '\n- Show that $\\cos{3\\theta}=4\\cos^3{\\theta}-3\\cos{\\theta}$. <span class="marks">[4]</span>  \n\nConsider the following function\n\n$$\n\\begin{align*}\n    f(x)&=4x^3-3x-\\cos{3k}\n\\end{align*}\n$$\n\nWhere $k$ is an angle in degrees such that $0 \\leq k \\leq 360^\\circ$.\n\n- Hence, verify that $\\cos{k}$ is one of the roots of $f(x)$.<span class="marks">[2]</span>  \n\nLet the remaining two roots of $f(x)$ be $\\alpha$ and $\\beta$.\n\n- \n  - Find $\\alpha\\beta$ in terms of $\\cos{k}$.\n  - Show that $\\beta=-\\alpha-\\cos k$.<span class="marks">[3]</span>\n\n\n- Using your answers from part (c) show that $\\alpha^2+\\alpha \\cos k +\\cos^2 k -\\tfrac{3}{4}=0$. <span class="marks">[2]</span>\n\n- Hence show that $\\alpha = \\frac{-\\cos k + \\sqrt{3}\\sin k}{2}$ and $\\beta = \\frac{-\\cos k - \\sqrt{3}\\sin k}{2}$. <span class="marks">[4]</span>\n\n\nIt is known that for $0 \\leq k \\leq 360^\\circ$ $f(x)$ has either $3$ distinct roots or a single distinct root and a repeated root.\n\n- Hence, find all of the values of $k$ for which $f(x)$ intersects the $x-$axis exactly $2$ times. <span class="marks">[7]</span>  \n',
    markScheme:
      "\n- Using the compound angle identity from the formula booklet we can write\n\n  $$\n  \\begin{align*}\n      \\cos{(A+B)}&=\\cos A \\cos B - \\sin A \\sin B\\\\[6pt]\n      \\cos{(2\\theta+\\theta)}&=\\cos 2\\theta \\cos \\theta - \\sin 2\\theta \\sin \\theta\\\\[6pt]\n      \\cos{3\\theta}&=\\cos 2\\theta \\cos \\theta - \\sin 2\\theta \\sin \\theta \\tag*{\\textbf{M1A1}}\n  \\end{align*}\n  $$\n\n  We can now the use the double angle formula to rewrite $\\cos {2\\theta}$ and $\\sin {2\\theta}$ in terms of single angle functions.\n\n  $$\n  \\begin{align*}\n      \\cos{3\\theta}&=(2\\cos^2{\\theta}-1) \\cos \\theta - (2\\sin{\\theta}\\cos{\\theta}) \\sin \\theta \\tag*{\\textbf{M1}}\\\\[6pt]\n      &=2\\cos^3\\theta-\\cos \\theta - 2\\sin^2{\\theta}\\cos{\\theta}\n  \\end{align*}\n  $$\n\n  Now rewrite $\\sin^2{\\theta}$ in terms of $\\cos{\\theta}$.\n\n  $$\n  \\begin{align*}\n      \\cos{3\\theta}&=2\\cos^3\\theta-\\cos \\theta - 2(1-\\cos^2{\\theta})\\cos{\\theta}\\tag*{\\textbf{M1}}\\\\[6pt]\n      &=2\\cos^3\\theta-\\cos \\theta - 2\\cos{\\theta}+2\\cos^3{\\theta}\\\\[6pt]\n      &=\\hspace{0.525em}\\answer{4\\cos^3\\theta-3\\cos \\theta} \\hspace{2em}\\text{... as required.}\n  \\end{align*}\n  $$\n\n- If $\\cos{k}$ is a root of $f(x)$ then $f(\\cos{k})=0$.\n\n  $$\n  \\begin{align*}\n      \\textcolor{white}{hack}\\tag*{\\textbf{A1}}\n  \\end{align*}\n  $$\n\n\n  $$\n  \\begin{align*}\n      f(\\cos{k})&=4(\\cos{k})^3-3(\\cos{k})-\\cos{3k}\n  \\end{align*}\n  $$\n\n  Using part (a)\n\n  $$\n  \\begin{align*}\n      f(\\cos{k})&=\\cos{3k}-\\cos{3k} \\tag*{\\textbf{M1}}\\\\[6pt]\n      &=0\n  \\end{align*}\n  $$\n\n  Hence, $\\answer{\\cos k \\text{ is a root of }f(x)}$\n- \n  - Using the formula for the product of the roots of a polynomial\n\n    $$\n    \\begin{align*}\n        \\alpha\\beta \\cos{k} &=-\\frac{(-1)^3\\cos{3k}}{4}  \\tag*{\\textbf{M1}}\n    \\end{align*}\n    $$\n\nUsing part (a) we can rewrite $\\cos{3k}$\n\n    $$\n    \\begin{align*}\n        \\alpha\\beta \\cos{k} &=\\frac{4\\cos^3{k}-3\\cos{k}}{4}\\\\[6pt]\n        \\alpha\\beta &= \\frac{4\\cos^2{k}-3}{4}\\\\[6pt]\n        &= \\hspace{0.525em}\\tcbhighmath{\\cos^2{k}-\\tfrac{3}{4}}  \\tag*{\\textbf{A1}}\n    \\end{align*}\n    $$\n\n  - Using the formula for the sum of the roots of a polynomial (with the coefficient of $x^2$ being $0$)\n\n    $$\n    \\begin{align*}\n        \\alpha + \\beta + \\cos k &=-\\frac{0}{4}\\\\[6pt]\n        \\beta= \\hspace{0.525em}\\tcbhighmath{-\\alpha - \\cos k}  \\tag*{\\textbf{A1}}\n    \\end{align*}\n    $$\n\n\n- Combining our answers from part (c)\n\n  $$\n  \\begin{align*}\n      \\alpha \\beta &= \\cos^2{k}-\\tfrac{3}{4} \\hspace{4em}\\beta= -\\alpha - \\cos k\\\\[6pt]\n      \\alpha(-\\alpha - \\cos k) &= \\cos^2{k}-\\tfrac{3}{4} \\tag*{\\textbf{(M1)}}\\\\[6pt]\n      -\\alpha^2-\\alpha \\cos{k} &= \\cos^2{k}-\\tfrac{3}{4}\\tag*{\\textbf{A1}}\\\\[6pt]\n      &\\hspace{0.4em}\\tcbhighmath{0=\\alpha^2+\\alpha \\cos{k}+\\cos^2{k}-\\tfrac{3}{4}} \\hspace{2em} \\text{... as required}\n  \\end{align*}\n  $$\n\n- Use the quadratic formula with $a=1, b=\\cos k$ and $c=\\cos^2 k - \\tfrac{3}{4}$\n\n  $$\n  \\begin{align*}\n      \\textcolor{white}{hack}\\tag*{\\textbf{A1}}\n  \\end{align*}\n  $$\n\n\n  $$\n  \\begin{align*}\n      \\alpha &=\\frac{-\\cos k \\pm \\sqrt{\\cos^2 k - 4\\times 1 \\times (\\cos^2 k - \\tfrac{3}{4})}}{2}\\tag*{\\textbf{A1}}\\\\[6pt]\n      &=\\frac{-\\cos k \\pm \\sqrt{\\cos^2 k - 4\\cos^2 k +3)}}{2}\\\\[6pt]\n      &=\\frac{-\\cos k \\pm \\sqrt{-3\\cos^2 k +3)}}{2}\\\\[6pt]\n      &=\\frac{-\\cos k \\pm \\sqrt{3(1-\\cos^2 k)}}{2}\\\\[6pt]\n      &=\\frac{-\\cos k \\pm \\sqrt{3\\sin^2 k}}{2}\\\\[6pt]\n      &=\\frac{-\\cos k \\pm \\sqrt{3}\\sin k}{2}\n  \\end{align*}\n  $$\n\n  Let $\\alpha = \\frac{-\\cos k + \\sqrt{3}\\sin k}{2}$, using the answer from part (c) (ii) we can find $\\beta$\n\n  $$\n  \\begin{align*}\n      \\textcolor{white}{hack}\\tag*{\\textbf{M1}}\n  \\end{align*}\n  $$\n\n\n  $$\n  \\begin{align*}\n      \\beta &= -\\alpha - \\cos{k}\\\\[6pt]\n      &= -\\frac{-\\cos k + \\sqrt{3}\\sin k}{2} - \\cos{k}\\\\[6pt]\n      &= \\frac{\\cos k - \\sqrt{3}\\sin k}{2} - \\frac{2\\cos{k}}{2}\\\\[6pt]\n      &=\\frac{-\\cos k - \\sqrt{3}\\sin k}{2}\n  \\end{align*}\n  $$\n\n  Hence $\\answer{\\alpha = \\frac{-\\cos k + \\sqrt{3}\\sin k}{2} \\text{ and } \\beta = \\frac{-\\cos k - \\sqrt{3}\\sin k}{2}}$\n\n  $$\n  \\begin{align*}\n      \\textcolor{white}{hack}\\tag*{\\textbf{A1}}\n  \\end{align*}\n  $$\n\n  Note: also accept vice versa solutions for $\\alpha$ and $\\beta$.\n- $f(x)$ must have a single distinct root and a repeated root to intersect the $x-$axis exactly twice.\n  Recall the three roots to $f(x)$ are $\\alpha, \\beta$ and $\\cos k$.\n  We have a repeated root when any of these conditions are met.\n\n  $$\n  \\begin{align*}\n      \\textcolor{white}{hack}\\tag*{\\textbf{M1}}\n  \\end{align*}\n  $$\n\n\n  $$\n  \\begin{align*}\n      \\alpha &= \\beta &[1]\\\\[6pt]\n      \\alpha &= \\cos k &[2]\\\\[6pt]\n      \\beta &= \\cos k &[3]\n  \\end{align*}\n  $$\n\n  Let's consider condition $[1]$ first\n\n  $$\n  \\begin{align*}\n      \\alpha &= \\beta\\\\[6pt]\n      \\frac{-\\cos k + \\sqrt{3}\\sin k}{2}&=\\frac{-\\cos k - \\sqrt{3}\\sin k}{2}\\tag*{\\textbf{M1}}\\\\[6pt]\n      \\frac{\\sqrt{3}\\sin k}{2}&=-\\frac{\\sqrt{3}\\sin k}{2}\\\\[6pt]\n      \\sin k&=0 \\hspace{2em} \\text{ where $0 \\leq k \\leq 360^\\circ$}\\\\[6pt]\n      k&=0, 180^\\circ, 360^\\circ \\tag*{\\textbf{A1}}\n  \\end{align*}\n  $$\n\n  Now consider condition $[2]$\n\n  $$\n  \\begin{align*}\n      \\alpha &= \\cos k\\\\[6pt]\n      \\frac{-\\cos k + \\sqrt{3}\\sin k}{2}&=\\cos k \\tag*{\\textbf{M1}}\\\\[6pt]\n      \\frac{-\\cos k + \\sqrt{3}\\sin k}{2}&=\\frac{2\\cos k}{2}\\\\[6pt]\n      \\frac{-3\\cos k + \\sqrt{3}\\sin k}{2}&=0\\\\[6pt]\n      \\sqrt{3}\\sin k&=3\\cos k\\\\[6pt]\n      \\tan k&= \\sqrt{3}\\hspace{2em} \\text{ where $0 \\leq k \\leq 360^\\circ$}\\\\[6pt]\n      k&=60^\\circ, 240^\\circ \\tag*{\\textbf{A1}}\n  \\end{align*}\n  $$\n\n  Finally consider condition $[3]$\n\n  $$\n  \\begin{align*}\n      \\beta &= \\cos k\\\\[6pt]\n      \\frac{-\\cos k - \\sqrt{3}\\sin k}{2}&=\\cos k \\tag*{\\textbf{M1}}\\\\[6pt]\n      \\tan k&= -\\sqrt{3}\\hspace{2em} \\text{ where $0 \\leq k \\leq 360^\\circ$}\\\\[6pt]\n      k&=120^\\circ, 300^\\circ \\tag*{\\textbf{A1}}\n  \\end{align*}\n  $$\n\n  Hence $f(x)$ will intersect the $x-$axis exactly $2$ times when\n\n  $$\n  \\begin{align*}\n      \\tcbhighmath{k=0^\\circ, 60^\\circ, 120^\\circ, 180^\\circ, 240^\\circ, 300^\\circ, 360^\\circ}\n  \\end{align*}\n  $$\n\n",
