    type: 'ERQ',
    title: 'Question 20',
    content:
      'The cubic polynomial equation $x^3 + bx^2 + cx + d = 0$ has three roots\n$x_1, x_2$ and $x_3$. By expanding the product $(x-x_1)(x-x_2)(x-x_3)$,\nshow that\n\n- \n  - $b = -(x_1+x_2+x_3)$;\n  - $c = x_1x_2 + x_1x_3 + x_2x_3$;\n  - $d = -x_1x_2x_3$. <span class="marks">[3]</span>\n\n\n\nIt is given that $b = -9$ and $c = 45$ for parts (b) and (c) below.\n\n- \n  - In the case that the three roots $x_1, x_2$ and $x_3$ form an\narithmetic\nsequence, show that one of the roots is $3$.\n  - Hence determine the value of $d$. <span class="marks">[5]</span>\n\n\n- In another case the three roots form a geometric sequence.\nDetermine\nthe value of $d$. <span class="marks">[6]</span>\n\n',
    markScheme:
      '\n- Given the three roots $x_1$, $x_2$ and $x_3$, we have\n\n  $$\n  \\begin{aligned}\n  x^3 + bx^2 + cx + d &= (x-x_1)(x-x_2)(x-x_3) \\\\[6pt]\n  &= (x^2 -(x_1+x_2)x + x_1x_2)(x-x_3) \\\\[8pt]\n  &= x^3 - (x_1+x_2+x_3)x^2 + (x_1x_2+x_1x_3+x_2x_3)x - x_1x_2x_3\\end{aligned}\n  $$\n\n  Hence, comparing the coefficients, we get\n  \n  - $\\answer{b = -(x_1+x_2+x_3)}$\n  - $\\answer{c = x_1x_2 + x_1x_3 + x_2x_3}$\n  - $\\answer{d = -x_1x_2x_3}$\n\n- \n  - Letting $\\alpha = x_1 + \\delta$, where $\\delta$ is the common\ndifference of the arithmetic sequence $x_1$, $x_2$, $x_3$, we\nhave\n\n    $$\n    \\begin{aligned}\n    \\hspace{1.8em} x_1  &=  \\alpha - \\delta \\\\[6pt]\n    x_2  &=  \\alpha \\\\[6pt]\n    x_3  &=  \\alpha + \\delta\\end{aligned}\n    $$\n\n    Hence, using part (a)\n(i), we get\n\n    $$\n    \\begin{aligned}\n    x_1 + x_2 + x_3 &= -b \\\\[6pt]\n    (\\alpha - \\delta) + \\alpha + (\\alpha + \\delta) &= -(-9) \\hspace{6em} \\\\[6pt]\n    3\\alpha &= 9 \\\\[6pt]\n    \\alpha &= 3 \\\\\n    \\end{aligned}\n    $$\n\n\n    $$\n    \\answer{x_2 = 3}\n    $$\n\n  - Using part (a) (ii), we have\n\n    $$\n    \\begin{aligned}\n    x_1x_2 + x_1x_3 + x_2x_3 &= c \\\\[6pt]\n    (3 - \\delta)(3) + (3 - \\delta)(3 + \\delta) + (3)(3 + \\delta) &= 45 \\\\[6pt]\n    27 - \\delta^2 &= 45 \\\\[6pt]\n    -\\delta^2 &= 18 \\\\[5pt]\n    \\delta &= \\sqrt{18}\\hspace{0.05em}{\\mathrm{\\hspace{0.05em}i}\\mkern 1mu}\\hspace{2em}\\end{aligned}\n    $$\n\n    Hence, using part (a) (iii), we get\n\n    $$\n    \\begin{aligned}\n    \\hspace{4em} d &= -x_1x_2x_3 \\\\[5pt]\n    &= -(3-\\sqrt{18}\\hspace{0.05em}{\\mathrm{\\hspace{0.05em}i}\\mkern 1mu})(3)(3+\\sqrt{18}\\hspace{0.05em}{\\mathrm{\\hspace{0.05em}i}\\mkern 1mu}) \\\\[6pt]\n    &\\answer{= -81}\\end{aligned}\n    $$\n\n\n- Letting $\\alpha = x_1$ and $r$ denote the common ratio of the\ngeometric sequence $x_1, x_2, x_3$, we have\n\n  $$\n  \\begin{aligned}\n  \\hspace{2.2em} x_1  &=  \\alpha \\\\[6pt]\n  x_2  &=  \\alpha r \\\\[6pt]\n  x_3  &=  \\alpha r^2\\end{aligned}\n  $$\n\n  Hence we get\n\n  $$\n  \\begin{aligned}\n  \\hspace{7.25em} x_1 + x_2 + x_3 &= -b \\hspace{3em} [\\text{by part (a) (i)}] \\\\[6pt]\n  \\alpha + \\alpha r + \\alpha r^2 &= -(-9) \\\\[6pt]\n  \\alpha (1+r+r^2) &= 9 \\qref{(1)}\\end{aligned}\n  $$\n\n  and\n\n  $$\n  \\begin{aligned}\n  x_1x_2 + x_1x_3 + x_2x_3 &= c \\hspace{3em} [\\text{by part (a) (ii)}] \\\\[6pt]\n  \\alpha (\\alpha r) + \\alpha (\\alpha r^2) + (\\alpha r)(\\alpha r^2) &= 45 \\\\[6pt]\n  \\alpha^2r(1+r+r^2) &= 45 \\qref{(2)}\\end{aligned}\n  $$\n\n  Taking the ratio\nof the expressions $(1)$ and $(2)$, we obtain\n\n  $$\n  \\begin{aligned}\n  \\dfrac{\\alpha^2r(\\cancel{1+r+r^2})}{\\alpha(\\cancel{1+r+r^2})} &= \\dfrac{45}{9} \\hspace{4em} \\\\[5pt]\n  \\dfrac{\\alpha^2r}{\\alpha} &= \\dfrac{45}{9} \\\\[15pt]\n  \\alpha r &= 5 \\qref{(3)}\\end{aligned}\n  $$\n\n  Hence, using the expression $(3)$, we find\n\n  $$\n  \\begin{aligned}\n  \\hspace{6.5em} d &= -x_1x_2x_3 \\hspace{3em} [\\text{by (a) (iii)}] \\\\[5pt]\n  &= -\\alpha (\\alpha r)(\\alpha r^2) \\\\[5pt]\n  &= -(\\alpha r)^3 \\\\[5pt]\n  &= -5^3 \\\\[6pt]\n  &\\answer{= -125}\\end{aligned}\n  $$\n\n',
