    title: 'Question 11',
    content:
      'The Fibonacci sequence is defined as follows:\n\n$$\n\\begin{aligned}\na_0 &= 0,\\hspace{0.25em} a_1 = 1,\\hspace{0.25em} a_2 = 1, \\\\[6pt]\na_n &= a_{n-1}+a_{n-2} \\hspace{0.5em}\\text{for}\\hspace{0.5em} n \\geq 2. \\qref{(FS)}\\end{aligned}\n$$\n\nProve by mathematical induction that\n$a_1^2+a_2^2+\\cdots+a_n^2=a_na_{n+1}$, where $n\\in\\mathbb{Z}^+$.',
    markScheme:
      'Let P$(n)$ be the following statement:\n\n$$\n\\begin{aligned}\n\\hspace{8.3em} a_1^2+a_2^2+...+a_n^2=a_na_{n+1} \\hspace{3em} [\\text{for $n \\in \\mathbb{Z}^+$}]\\end{aligned}\n$$\n\nUsing mathematical induction, we will prove that P$(n)$ holds for all\n$n \\in \\mathbb{Z}^+$.\nBase case. For $n = 1$, we have\n\n$$\n\\begin{aligned}\na_1^2 &= 1^2 \\\\[6pt]\n&= 1\\cdot 1 \\\\[6pt]\n&= a_1a_2\\end{aligned}\n$$\n\nHence P$(1)$ holds.\nInductive hypothesis. We assume that P$(k)$ holds for some\n$k \\geq 1$. In other words, we assume that\n\n$$\n\\begin{aligned}\na_1^2+a_2^2+...+a_k^2 = a_ka_{k+1} \\qref{(IH)}\\end{aligned}\n$$\n\nfor some\n$k \\geq 1$.\nInductive step. To show that P$(k+1)$ holds, we need to\nshow that\n\n$$\n\\begin{aligned}\na_1^2+a_2^2+...+a_k^2 + a_{k+1}^2= a_{k+1}a_{k+2} \\hspace{2.2em} \\qref{(1)}\\end{aligned}\n$$\n\nFrom the left hand side of the equation $(1)$, we obtain\n\n$$\n\\begin{aligned}\na_1^2+a_2^2+...+a_k^2 + a_{k+1}^2 &= \\big(a_1^2+a_2^2+...+a_k^2\\big) + a_{k+1}^2 \\\\[6pt]\n&= a_ka_{k+1} + a_{k+1}^2 \\hspace{3em} [\\text{by (IH)}] \\\\[7pt]\n&= \\big(a_k + a_{k+1}\\big)a_{k+1} \\\\[7pt]\n&= a_{k+2}a_{k+1} \\hspace{3em} [\\text{by (FS)}] \\\\[7pt]\n&= a_{k+1}a_{k+2}\\end{aligned}\n$$\n\nHence P$(k+1)$ holds as well.\nConclusion. P$(1)$ holds, and for every $k \\geq 1$, if\nP$(k)$ holds then P$(k+1)$ also holds.\nHence, by mathematical induction, we conclude that P$(n)$ holds for all\n$n \\in \\mathbb{Z}^+$.',
