    type: 'SAQ',
    title: 'Question 14',
    content:
      'Use mathematical induction to prove that $n^3-9n^2+26n-24$ is divisible by $6$ for all $n\\geq 5$.',
    markScheme:
      'Let $P(n)$ be the proposition that $n^3-9n^2+26n-24$ is divisible by $6$.\nThe first step is to verify the base case ($n=5$).\n\n$$\n\\begin{align*}\n    P(5)&=(5)^3-9(5)^2+26(5)-24\\\\\n    &=6\n\\end{align*}\n$$\n\n$P(5)$ is divisible by $6$ therefore it is true.\n\n$$\n    \\tag*{\\textbf{A1}}\n$$\n\n$\\textcolor{white}{gap}$\nNow we will form the assumption.\nAssume $P(k)$ is true.\n\n$$\n\\begin{align*}\n    P(k)&=k^3-9k^2+26k-24\\\\\n    &=6A  \\tag*{\\textbf{M1}}\n\\end{align*}\n$$\n\nWhere $k, A\\in \\mathbb{Z^+}$ and $k\\geq5$.\nNow we will consider the $(k+1)^{\\text{th}}$ case and by using the assumption we will show that $P(k+1)$ is divisible by $6$.\n\n$$\n\\begin{align*}\n    P(k+1)&=(k+1)^3-9(k+1)^2+26(k+1)-24\\\\\n    &=\\bm{k^3}+3k^2+3k+1-\\bm{9k^2}-18k-9+\\bm{26k}+26-\\bm{24} \\tag*{\\textbf{M1}}\n\\end{align*}\n$$\n\nThe terms in bold above are equivalent to the assumption, $P(k)$. Hence we can replace them with $6A$ and then simplify. This is known as the inductive step as we are inducting the assumption into the proof.\n\n$$\n\\begin{align*}\n    P(k+1)&=3k^2+3k+1-18k-9+26+6A \\tag*{\\textbf{A1}}\\\\\n    &=6A+3k^2-15k+18\n\\end{align*}\n$$\n\nWe now need to show the remaining terms involving $k$ are divisible by $6$.\n\n$$\n\\begin{align*}\n    P(k+1)&=6A+3(k-2)(k-3) \n\\end{align*}\n$$\n\nAfter factorising we can see that the expression $(k-2)(k-3)$ is the product of two consecutive numbers (recall $k\\geq5$). This will always be an even number, hence we can replace it with $2B$, Where $B \\in \\mathbb{Z^+}$.\n\n$$\n\\begin{align*}\n    P(k+1)&=6A+3\\times 2B\\\\\n    &=6A + 6B\\\\\n    &=6(A+B)\n\\end{align*}\n$$\n\n$P(k+1)$ is divisible by $6$.\n\n$$\n    \\tag*{\\textbf{R1}}\n$$\n\n$\\textcolor{white}{gap}$\nWe must write a concluding sentence.\n\n$$\n\\answer{\\text{$P(5)$ is true and $P(k)$ being true implies $P(k+1)$ is true. We can therefore say, by the principle of mathematical induction, that $P(n)$ is true for all $n\\geq 5$.}}\n$$\n\n\n$$\n    \\tag*{\\textbf{R1}}\n$$\n\n$\\textcolor{white}{gap}$',
