    content:
      '\n- Show that\n$\\dfrac{1}{2\\sqrt{n+1}} < \\sqrt{n+1} - \\sqrt{n}$,\nwhere $n \\in \\mathbb{Z},\\hspace{0.1em} n\\geq 0$. <span class="marks">[3]</span>\n\n- Hence show that $\\dfrac{1}{\\sqrt{2}} < 2\\sqrt{2} - 2$.\n<span class="marks">[2]</span>\n\n- Prove by mathematical induction that\n\n  $$\n  \\hspace{4em} \\sum_{r = 2}^n \\dfrac{1}{\\sqrt{r}} < 2\\sqrt{n} - 2 \\hspace{2em} \\text{for all $n \\in \\mathbb{Z}^+$, $n \\geq 2$.}\n  \n  $$\n\n  <span class="marks">[9]</span>\n\n',
    markScheme:
      '\n- For any $n \\in \\mathbb{Z},\\hspace{0.1em} n \\geq 0$, we have\n\n  $$\n  \\begin{aligned}\n  \\hspace{3em} \\sqrt{n+1} - \\sqrt{n} &= \\left[\\dfrac{\\sqrt{n+1} - \\sqrt{n}}{1}\\right] \\left[\\dfrac{\\sqrt{n+1} + \\sqrt{n}}{\\sqrt{n+1} + \\sqrt{n}}\\right] \\\\[6pt]\n  &= \\dfrac{(\\cancel{n}+1) - \\cancel{n}}{\\sqrt{n+1} + \\sqrt{n}} \\\\[6pt]\n  &= \\dfrac{1}{\\sqrt{n+1} + \\sqrt{n}}\\end{aligned}\n  $$\n\n  Hence we get\n\n  $$\n  \\begin{aligned}\n  \\hspace{7.8em} \\dfrac{1}{2\\sqrt{n+1}} < \\dfrac{1}{\\sqrt{n+1} + \\sqrt{n}} \\hspace{2em} \\big[\\text{since $\\sqrt{n+1} > \\sqrt{n}$}\\hspace{0.1em}\\big]\\end{aligned}\n  $$\n\n\n  $$\n  \\answer{\\dfrac{1}{2\\sqrt{n+1}} < \\sqrt{n+1} - \\sqrt{n}} \\hspace{3.8em} \\qref{(1)}\n  $$\n\n- Hence, substituting $n = 1$ in the inequality $(1)$, we obtain\n\n  $$\n  \\begin{aligned}\n  \\dfrac{1}{2\\sqrt{2}} &< \\sqrt{2} - 1 \\hspace{1em}\\end{aligned}\n  $$\n\n\n  $$\n  \\answer{\\dfrac{1}{\\sqrt{2}} < 2\\sqrt{2} - 2}\n  $$\n\n- Let P$(n)$ be the following statement:\n\n  $$\n  \\begin{aligned}\n  \\hspace{6em} \\sum_{r = 2}^n \\dfrac{1}{\\sqrt{r}} < 2\\sqrt{n} - 2 \\hspace{3em} [\\text{for $n\\geq2$}]\\end{aligned}\n  $$\n\n  Using math induction, we will prove that P$(n)$\n$\\text{holds for all \\(n \\in \\mathbb{Z}^+\\), \\(n\\geq2\\).}$\n  Base case. For $n = 2$, from part (b), we have\n\n  $$\n  \\begin{aligned}\n  \\dfrac{1}{\\sqrt{2}} < 2\\sqrt{2} - 2\\end{aligned}\n  $$\n\n  Hence P$(2)$\nholds.\n  Inductive hypothesis. We assume that P$(k)$ holds for\nsome $k \\geq 2$. In other words, we assume that\n\n  $$\n  \\begin{aligned}\n  \\sum_{r = 2}^k \\dfrac{1}{\\sqrt{r}} < 2\\sqrt{k} - 2 \\hspace{1.5em} \\qref{(IH)}\\end{aligned}\n  $$\n\n  for some $k \\geq 2$.\n  Inductive step. To show that P$(k+1)$ holds, we need\nto show that\n\n  $$\n  \\begin{aligned}\n  \\hspace{0.2em} \\sum_{r = 2}^{k+1} \\dfrac{1}{\\sqrt{r}} < 2\\sqrt{k+1} - 2 \\qref{(2)}\\end{aligned}\n  $$\n\n\nFrom the left hand side of the inequality $(2)$, we obtain\n\n$$\n\\begin{aligned}\n\\hspace{8em} \\sum_{r = 2}^{k+1} \\dfrac{1}{\\sqrt{r}} &= \\dfrac{1}{\\sqrt{k+1}} + \\sum_{r = 2}^k \\dfrac{1}{\\sqrt{r}} \\\\[6pt]\n&< \\dfrac{1}{\\sqrt{k+1}} + \\big(2\\sqrt{k} - 2\\big) \\hspace{2em} [\\text{by (IH)}] \\\\[12pt]\n&< \\big(2\\sqrt{k+1} - \\cancel{2\\sqrt{k}}\\big) + \\big(\\cancel{2\\sqrt{k}} - 2\\big) \\hspace{2em} [\\text{by part (a)}] \\\\[18pt]\n&= 2\\sqrt{k+1} -2\\end{aligned}\n$$\n\nHence P$(k+1)$ holds as well.\nConclusion. P$(2)$ holds, and for every $k \\geq 2$, if\nP$(k)$ holds then P$(k+1)$ also holds.\nHence, by mathematical induction, we conclude that\nP$(n)$ holds for all $\\text{\\(n\\hspace{-0.2em}\\in\\hspace{-0.2em}\\mathbb{Z}^+\\hspace{-0.2em},\\hspace{0.05em}n\\hspace{-0.2em}\\geq\\hspace{-0.2em}2\\)}$.',
