    content:
      'Let $f(x) = (x-1)e^{\\frac{x}{3}}$, for $x \\in \\mathbb{R}$.\n\n- Find $f\'(x)$.  <span class="marks">[2]</span>\n\n- Prove by induction that\n$\\dfrac{\\mathrm{d}^nf}{\\mathrm{d}x^n} = \\bigg(\\dfrac{3n + x - 1}{3^n}\\bigg)e^{\\frac{x}{3}}$\nfor all $n \\in \\mathbb{Z}^+$.  <span class="marks">[7]</span>\n\n- Find the coordinates of any local maximum and minimum points on the\ngraph of $y = f(x)$. Justify whether such point is a maximum or a\nminimum. <span class="marks">[5]</span>\n\n- Find the coordinates of any points of inflexion on the graph of\n$y = f(x)$. Justify whether such point is a point of inflexion.\n<span class="marks">[5]</span>\n\n- Hence sketch the graph of $y = f(x)$, indicating clearly the points\nfound in parts (c) and (d) and any intercepts with the axes.\n<span class="marks">[4]</span>\n\n',
    markScheme:
      "\n- Using the product rule, we get\n\n  $$\n  \\begin{aligned}\n  f'(x) &= \\dfrac{\\mathrm{d}}{\\mathrm{d}x}\\big[(x-1)e^{\\frac{x}{3}}\\big] \\\\[6pt]\n  &= e^{\\frac{x}{3}} + \\dfrac{1}{3}(x-1)e^{\\frac{x}{3}} \\\\[6pt]\n  &\\answer{= \\bigg(\\dfrac{x+2}{3}\\bigg)e^{\\frac{x}{3}}}\\end{aligned}\n  $$\n\n- Let P$(n)$ be the following statement:\n\n  $$\n  \\begin{aligned}\n  \\hspace{8.7em} \\dfrac{\\mathrm{d}^nf}{\\mathrm{d}x^n} = \\bigg(\\dfrac{3n + x - 1}{3^n}\\bigg)e^{\\frac{x}{3}} \\hspace{3em} [\\text{for $n \\in \\mathbb{Z}^+$}]\\end{aligned}\n  $$\n\n  Using mathematical induction, we will prove that P$(n)$ holds for\nall $n \\in \\mathbb{Z}^+$.\n\nBase case. For $n = 1$, from part (a), we have\n\n$$\n\\begin{aligned}\n\\dfrac{\\mathrm{d}f}{\\mathrm{d}x} = \\bigg(\\dfrac{3 + x - 1}{3}\\bigg)e^{\\frac{x}{3}} \\end{aligned}\n$$\n\nHence P$(1)$ holds.\nInductive hypothesis. We assume that P$(k)$ holds for some\n$k \\geq 1$. In other words, we assume that\n\n$$\n\\begin{aligned}\n\\hspace{0.1em} \\dfrac{\\mathrm{d}^kf}{\\mathrm{d}x^k} = \\bigg(\\dfrac{3k + x - 1}{3^k}\\bigg)e^{\\frac{x}{3}} \\qref{(IH)}\\end{aligned}\n$$\n\nfor some $k \\geq 1$.\nInductive step. To show that P$(k+1)$ holds, we need to\nshow that\n\n$$\n\\begin{aligned}\n\\hspace{1.2em} \\dfrac{\\mathrm{d}^{k+1}f}{\\mathrm{d}x^{k+1}} = \\bigg[\\dfrac{3(k+1) + x - 1}{3^{k+1}}\\bigg]e^{\\frac{x}{3}}\\end{aligned}\n$$\n\nIf we differentiate both sides of the equation (IH), we obtain\n\n$$\n\\begin{aligned}\n\\hspace{4.9em} \\dfrac{\\mathrm{d}^{k+1}f}{\\mathrm{d}x^{k+1}} &= \\dfrac{\\mathrm{d}}{\\mathrm{d}x}\\bigg[\\bigg(\\dfrac{3k + x - 1}{3^k}\\bigg)e^{\\frac{x}{3}}\\bigg] \\\\[6pt]\n&= \\bigg(\\dfrac{1}{3^k}\\bigg)e^{\\frac{x}{3}} + \\dfrac{1}{3}\\bigg(\\dfrac{3k + x - 1}{3^k}\\bigg)e^{\\frac{x}{3}} \\\\[6pt]\n&= \\bigg[\\dfrac{1}{3^k} + \\dfrac{3k + x - 1}{3^{k+1}}\\bigg]e^{\\frac{x}{3}} \\\\[6pt]\n&= \\bigg[\\dfrac{3(k+1) + x - 1}{3^{k+1}}\\bigg]e^{\\frac{x}{3}}\\end{aligned}\n$$\n\nHence P$(k+1)$ holds as well.\nConclusion. P$(1)$ holds, and for every $k \\geq 1$, if\nP$(k)$ holds then P$(k+1)$ also holds.\nHence, by mathematical induction, we conclude that P$(n)$ holds for all\n$n \\in \\mathbb{Z}^+$.\n\n- If we solve the equation $f'(x) = 0$ for $x$, we get\n\n  $$\n  \\begin{aligned}\n  \\bigg(\\dfrac{x + 2}{3}\\bigg)e^{\\frac{x}{3}} &= 0 \\\\[6pt]\n  x + 2 &= 0 \\\\[12pt] \n  x &= -2\\end{aligned}\n  $$\n\n  Hence $-2$ is the only critical number of\n$f$.\n  Using the ID Test, we have\n  ![SkillUpp Image](https://assets.revisionvillage.com/public/question/3446dd1a-9a13-43e5-8af3-ee3cf0e76f4c/images/6df8b040-2aba-4405-8103-6cc64148c86f/41f59f91431e030c029eab143139497c30f1df01.svg)\n\n\n  The sign of $f'$ changes from negative to positive at $-2$.\n  Hence, by the First Derivative Test, $f$ has a local minimum at\n$-2$.\n  Evaluating $y = f(x)$ for $x = -2$, we find\n\n  $$\n  \\begin{aligned}\n  y &= f(-2) \\\\[6pt]\n  &= (-2-1)e^{-\\frac{2}{3}} \\\\[6pt]\n  &= -3e^{-\\frac{2}{3}}\\end{aligned}\n  $$\n\n  Hence the graph of $y = f(x)$\nhas a local minimum at\n$\\answer{\\mathrm{A}\\big(\\hspace{-0.2em}-2,-3e^{-\\frac{2}{3}}\\big)}$.\n- If we solve the equation $f''(x) = 0$ for $x$, we get\n\n  $$\n  \\begin{aligned}\n  \\bigg[\\dfrac{3(2) + x - 1}{3^2}\\bigg]e^{\\frac{x}{3}} &= 0 \\\\[6pt]  \n  3(2) + x - 1 &= 0 \\\\[12pt] \n  x &= -5\\end{aligned}\n  $$\n\n  Hence there is at most one point of inflexion\non the graph of $y = f(x)$.\n  Using the Concavity Test, we have\n  ![SkillUpp Image](https://assets.revisionvillage.com/public/question/3446dd1a-9a13-43e5-8af3-ee3cf0e76f4c/images/44ae7137-2675-4b13-8b95-c1dd8eee70fc/1c4ca00263d0aa013c934479ae539a797857f949.svg)\n\n\n  The graph of $y = f(x)$ changes concavity from downward to upward at\n$-5$.\n  Hence the graph of $y = f(x)$ has an inflexion point at $-5$.\n  Evaluating $y = f(x)$ for $x = -5$, we find\n\n  $$\n  \\begin{aligned}\n  y &= f(-5) \\\\[6pt]\n  &= (-5-1)e^{-\\frac{5}{3}} \\\\[6pt]\n  &= -6e^{-\\frac{5}{3}}\\end{aligned}\n  $$\n\n  Hence the graph of $y = f(x)$\nhas the inflexion point at\n$\\answer{\\mathrm{B}\\big(\\hspace{-0.2em}-5,-6e^{-\\frac{5}{3}}\\big)}$.\n- We first note that the domain of the function\n$f(x) = (x-1)e^{\\frac{x}{3}}$ is $(-\\infty,\\infty)$.\n  Solving the equation $f(x) = 0$ for $x$, we get\n\n  $$\n  \\begin{aligned}\n  (x-1)e^{\\frac{x}{3}} &= 0 \\\\[6pt]\n  x-1 &= 0 \\\\[6pt]\n  x &= 1\\end{aligned}\n  $$\n\n  Hence the point\n$\\answer{\\mathrm{C}(1,0)}$\nis the $x$-intercept of the graph of $y = f(x)$.\n  Evaluating $y = f(x)$ for $x = 0$, we find\n\n  $$\n  \\begin{aligned}\n  y &= f(0) \\\\[6pt]\n  &= (0-1)e^{0} \\\\[6pt]\n  &= -1\\end{aligned}\n  $$\n\n  Hence the point\n$\\answer{\\mathrm{D}(0,-1)}$\nis the $y$-intercept of the graph of $y = f(x)$.\n  We have\n\n  $$\n  \\begin{aligned}\n  \\lim_{x\\rightarrow -\\infty} f(x) &= \\lim_{x\\rightarrow -\\infty} \\big[(x-1)e^{\\frac{x}{3}}\\big] \\\\[6pt]\n  &= 0\\end{aligned}\n  $$\n\n  and\n\n  $$\n  \\begin{aligned}\n  \\lim_{x\\rightarrow \\infty} f(x) &= \\lim_{x\\rightarrow \\infty} \\big[(x-1)e^{\\frac{x}{3}}\\big] \\\\[6pt]\n  &= \\infty\\end{aligned}\n  $$\n\n  Hence the $x$-axis is a horizontal\nasymptote of the graph of $y = f(x)$.\n  If we sketch the graph of $y = f(x)$ indicating the points A, B, C &\nD, we have\n  ![SkillUpp Image](https://assets.revisionvillage.com/public/question/3446dd1a-9a13-43e5-8af3-ee3cf0e76f4c/images/42de9ed9-4fa4-4579-a350-33bfc21dab44/2fc0df9fcb42d39dca43193d481d73ca1795c4bb.svg)\n\n\n",
