    content:
      'The following diagram shows the graph of\n$y=\\arctan(2x-3)+\\dfrac{3\\pi}{4}$ for $x\\in \\mathbb{R}$,\nwith asymptotes at $y=\\dfrac{\\pi}{4}$ and $y=\\dfrac{5\\pi}{4}$.\n![SkillUpp Image](https://assets.revisionvillage.com/public/question/94f32658-f1f8-4e8a-a7ec-64540cbb0149/images/f7349dc1-1bf4-4e25-a560-7f6b11100f20/081334c23d135e25efc729fff5cf10e0f4fe7363.svg)\n\n\n\n- Describe a sequence of transformations that transforms the graph of\n$y=\\arctan x$ to the graph of $y=\\arctan(2x-3)+\\dfrac{3\\pi}{4}$ for\n$x\\in \\mathbb{R}$.<span class="marks">[3]</span>\n\n- Show that\n$\\arctan p - \\arctan q \\equiv \\arctan \\left(\\dfrac{p-q}{1+pq}\\right)$.<span class="marks">[3]</span>\n\n- Verify that\n$\\arctan(x+2)-\\arctan(x+1) = \\arctan\\left( \\dfrac{1}{(x+1)^2+(x+1)+1}\\right)$.<span class="marks">[3]</span>\n\n- Using mathematical induction and the results from part (b) and\n(c), prove that<span class="marks">[8]</span>\n\n\n  $$\n  \\sum_{r=1}^n \\arctan\\left(\\dfrac{1}{r^2+r+1}\\right) = \\arctan(n+1)-\\dfrac{\\pi}{4} \\hspace{0.8em} \\text{for } n\\in \\mathbb{Z}^{+}.\n  $$\n\n',
    markScheme:
      '\n- The function can be expressed as\n$y=\\arctan\\left(2\\left(x-\\dfrac{3}{2}\\right)\\right)+\\dfrac{3\\pi}{4}$,\nhence we get the following transformations in order\n\n  $$\n  \\begin{aligned}\n  \\text{transformation $1$}&: \\hspace{0.5em}\\hspace{0.525em}\\answer{\\text{horizontal stretch by a factor of $\\dfrac{1}{2}$}} \\\\[10pt]\n  \\text{transformation $2$}&:\n  \\hspace{0.5em}\\hspace{0.525em}\\answer{\\text{horizontal translation $\\dfrac{3}{2}$ units right}}\\\\[10pt]\n  \\text{transformation $3$}&: \\hspace{0.5em}\\hspace{0.525em}\\answer{\\text{vertical translation $\\dfrac{3\\pi}{4}$ units up}}\\end{aligned}\n  $$\n\n  Note that the vertical shift, which is transformation $3$, can also be performed before the horizontal transformations.\n- Using the compound angle identity, we get\n\n  $$\n  \\begin{aligned}\n  \\tan\\left(\\arctan p - \\arctan q \\right) &= \\dfrac{\\tan(\\arctan p)-\\tan(\\arctan q)}{1+\\tan(\\arctan p)\\tan(\\arctan q)} \\\\[12pt]\n  &=\\dfrac{p-q}{1+pq} \\\\[12pt]\\\\\n  \\intertext{Finally, taking the $\\arctan$ on both sides}\\\\\n  &\\hspace{-2.85cm}\\answer{\\arctan p - \\arctan q \\equiv \\arctan \\left(\\dfrac{p-q}{1+pq}\\right)}\\end{aligned}\n  $$\n\n- Using the formula from part (b), we obtain\n\n  $$\n  \\begin{aligned}\n  \\arctan(x+2)-\\arctan(x+1) &= \\arctan\\left(\\dfrac{(x+2)-(x+1)}{1+(x+2)(x+1)}\\right)\\\\[12pt]\n  &= \\arctan\\left(\\dfrac{1}{((x+1)+1)(x+1)+1}\\right)\\\\[12pt]\n  &\\hspace{0.2em}\\answer{=\\arctan\\left(\\dfrac{1}{(x+1)^2+(x+1)+1}\\right)} \\end{aligned}\n  $$\n\n- Let $\\mathrm{P}(n)$ be the following statement:\n\n  $$\n  \\begin{aligned}\n  \\sum_{r=1}^n \\arctan\\left(\\dfrac{1}{r^2+r+1}\\right) &= \\arctan(n+1)-\\dfrac{\\pi}{4} \\hspace{3em} \\big[\\,\\text{for all $n \\in \\mathbb{Z}^{+}$}\\,\\big]\\end{aligned}\n  $$\n\n  Using mathematical induction, we will prove that $\\mathrm{P}(n)$\nholds for all $n \\in \\mathbb{Z}^{+}$.\n  Base case. For $n = 1$, from part (a), we have\n\n  $$\n  \\begin{aligned}\n  \\arctan\\left(\\dfrac{1}{(1)^2+1+1}\\right) &= \\arctan\\left(\\dfrac{1}{3}\\right) \\\\[10pt]\n  &= \\arctan(2)-\\arctan(1) \\hspace{3em} \\big[\\text{by part (b,c)}\\big]\\\\[12pt]\n  &= \\arctan(2)-\\dfrac{\\pi}{4}\\end{aligned}\n  $$\n\n  Hence P$(1)$ holds.\n  Inductive hypothesis. We assume that $\\mathrm{P}(k)$\nholds for some $k \\geq 1$. In other words, we assume that\n\n  $$\n  \\begin{aligned}\n  \\sum_{r=1}^k \\arctan\\left(\\dfrac{1}{r^2+r+1}\\right) = \\arctan(k+1)-\\dfrac{\\pi}{4} \\hspace{0.5em} \\qref{(IH)}\\end{aligned}\n  $$\n\n  for some $k \\geq 1$.\n  Inductive step. To show that $\\mathrm{P}(k+1)$ holds,\nwe need to show that\n\n  $$\n  \\begin{aligned}\n  \\sum_{r=1}^{k+1} \\arctan\\left(\\dfrac{1}{r^2+r+1}\\right) = \\arctan(k+2)-\\dfrac{\\pi}{4}\\end{aligned}\n  $$\n\n  If we add the $k+1$ term to both sides of the equation (IH), we\nobtain\n\n  $$\n  \\begin{aligned}\n  \\sum_{r=1}^{k+1} \\arctan\\left(\\dfrac{1}{r^2+r+1}\\right) &= \\arctan(k+1)-\\dfrac{\\pi}{4} + \\arctan\\left(\\dfrac{1}{(k+1)^2+(k+1)+1}\\right)\\\\[10pt]\n  \\big[\\text{by part (c)}\\big]\\hspace{3em} &= \\arctan(k+2) - \\arctan(k+1) + \\arctan(k+1)-\\dfrac{\\pi}{4}\\\\[12pt]\n  &= \\arctan(k+2)-\\dfrac{\\pi}{4}\\end{aligned}\n  $$\n\n  Hence $P(k+1)$ holds\nas well.\n  Conclusion. P$(1)$ holds, and for every $k \\geq 1$, if\nP$(k)$ holds then P$(k+1)$ also holds.\n  Hence, by mathematical induction, we conclude that P$(n)$ holds for\nall $n \\in \\mathbb{Z}^{+}$.\n',
