    content:
      'Consider $f(x) = \\dfrac{1}{2} - \\ln\\left(\\sqrt{x^2-4}\\right)$.\n\n- Find the largest possible domain $D$ for $f$ to be a function.\n<span class="marks">[2]</span>\n\n\nThe function $f$ is defined by\n$f(x) = \\dfrac{1}{2} - \\ln\\left(\\sqrt{x^2-4}\\right)$, for $x \\in D$.\n\n- Sketch the graph of $y = f(x)$, showing clearly the\nequations of asymptotes and the coordinates of any intercepts with\nthe axes. <span class="marks">[3]</span>\n\n- Explain why $f$ is an even function. <span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n- Explain why the inverse function $f^{-1}$ does not exist.\n<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n\nThe function $g$ is defined by\n$g(x) = \\dfrac{1}{2} - \\ln\\left(\\sqrt{x^2-4}\\right)$, for\n$x \\in (2,\\infty)$.\n\n- Find the inverse function $g^{-1}$ and state its domain.\n<span class="marks">[4]</span>  \n',
    markScheme:
      '\n- The square root function is defined on $[0,\\infty)$ and natural\nlogarithm function is defined on $(0,\\infty)$.\n  Hence $f$ is a function if\n\n  $$\n  \\begin{aligned}\n  \\textstyle \\sqrt{x^2-4} &> 0 \\hspace{2em} \\\\[6pt]\n  x^2-4 &> 0 \\\\[6pt]\n  x^2 &> 4 \\\\[6pt]\n  |x| &> 2 \\\\[6pt]\n  x < -2 \\hspace{0.5em}&\\hspace{0.2em}\\text{or}\\hspace{0.7em} x > 2\\end{aligned}\n  $$\n\n  Hence the largest possible domain for $f$ to be a function is\n\n  $$\n  \\begin{aligned}\n  \\answer{D = (-\\infty,-2)\\cup(2,\\infty)}\\end{aligned}\n  $$\n\n- If we sketch the graph of $y = f(x)$ [by using G.D.C.], we have\n  ![SkillUpp Image](https://assets.revisionvillage.com/public/question/18ea91ad-1794-4924-860f-5cce1a2aaaa5/images/52aadecb-f956-431e-9b31-87bfc4bc127b/c292af76cbb30669709b70ec8dbfa255472cb0f7.svg)\n\n\n- $\\answer{\\text{The function \\(f\\) is even because its graph is symmetric about the \\(y\\)-axis.}}$\n  OR\n  $\\answer{\\text{The function \\(f\\) is even because it satisfies \\(f(x) = f(-x)\\) for all \\(x \\in D\\).}}$\n- $\\answer{\\text{The inverse function \\(f^{-1}\\) does not exist because \\(f\\) is not bijective.}}$\n- If we solve the equation $(g\\circ g^{-1})(x) = x$ for\n$y = g^{-1}(x)$, we get\n\n  $$\n  \\begin{aligned}\n  g(g^{-1}(x)) &= x \\\\[15pt]\n  g(y) &= x \\\\[10pt]\n  \\dfrac{1}{2} - \\textstyle \\ln\\hspace{-0.1em}\\big(\\sqrt{y^2-4}\\big) &= x \\\\[6pt]\n  \\textstyle \\ln\\hspace{-0.1em}\\big(\\sqrt{y^2-4}\\big) &= \\dfrac{1}{2} - x  \\\\[9pt]\n  \\textstyle \\sqrt{y^2-4} &= e^{\\left(\\frac{1}{2} - x\\right)} \\\\[12pt]\n  y^2-4 &= e^{2\\left(\\frac{1}{2} - x\\right)} \\\\[14pt]\n  y^2 &= e^{1 - 2x} + 4 \\\\[13pt]\n  y &= \\textstyle \\sqrt{e^{1 - 2x} + 4} \\hspace{2.7em} \\\\\n  \\end{aligned}\n  $$\n\n  Hence an expression for $g^{-1}$ is\n$\\answer{g^{-1}(x) = \\sqrt{e^{1 - 2x} + 4}}$\n  The domain of $g^{-1}$ is\n$\\answer{\\mathbb{R}}$\n',
