    content:
      'The graph of $y=f(x)$ for $0\\leq x \\leq 6$ is shown below\n![SkillUpp Image](https://assets.revisionvillage.com/public/question/c12c7015-df65-4beb-b764-cc77e7025623/images/d9b698f4-a101-40b3-a118-dbc3aa80bdc7/AA1279-q1.JPEG)\n\n\nThe odd function $h(x)$ has the domain $-6\\leq x \\leq 6$ and $h(x)=2f(x)$ for $0\\leq x \\leq 6$.\n\n- Sketch $h(x)$ on the axes above.<span class="marks">[2]</span>  \n\n$f(x)$ is shown again below.\n![SkillUpp Image](https://assets.revisionvillage.com/public/question/c12c7015-df65-4beb-b764-cc77e7025623/images/3a60566c-11b7-4cc2-ac58-301a1f0b734a/AA1279-q2.JPEG)\n\n\n\n- Sketch the graph of $y=[f(x)]^2$ on the axes above.<span class="marks">[3]</span>  \n\n$f(x)$ is shown one more time below.\n![SkillUpp Image](https://assets.revisionvillage.com/public/question/c12c7015-df65-4beb-b764-cc77e7025623/images/6712f3c3-7980-49b2-be9d-09510dd7213d/AA1279-q3.JPEG)\n\n\n\n- Sketch the graph of $y=\\dfrac{1}{f(x)}$ on the axes above.<span class="marks">[3]</span>  \n',
    markScheme:
      "\n- Let's start with graphing $y=2f(x)$.\n  This is a vertical stretch by a scale factor of 2.\n  The distance of all $y-$coordinates from the $x-$axis are multiplied by two.\n  The key point $(2, 2)$ will become $(2, 4)$.  This is shown in the graph below in $\\textcolor{red}{\\text{red}}$.\n  ![SkillUpp Image](https://assets.revisionvillage.com/public/question/c12c7015-df65-4beb-b764-cc77e7025623/images/ee8f2b59-189d-4582-b80f-8543d1539c11/AA1279-a1.JPEG)\n\n\n  The definition of an odd function is $f(-x)=-f(x)$. This transformation represents rotational symmetry of order $2$ about the origin which is equivalent to performing two reflections, one in each axis, in any order.\n  Therefore, to complete the rest of the graph of $h(x)$, we can either take the graph of $y=2f(x)$ and rotate it $180^\\circ$ about the origin or perform two reflections, one in each axis. Both result in the same final position.\n  If we consider the reflection approach. First, we perform $f(x) \\rightarrow f(-x)$, this is a reflection in the $y-$axis. This is the dotted blue line shown in the following graph.\n  Then we consider $f(-x)\\rightarrow-f(-x)$, this is a reflection in the $x-$axis.\n  This fully transformed part is shown in solid $\\textcolor{blue}{\\text{blue}}$ in the following graph.\n  ![SkillUpp Image](https://assets.revisionvillage.com/public/question/c12c7015-df65-4beb-b764-cc77e7025623/images/e98b48c5-6b88-483c-9505-e090a80ebdda/AA1279-a2.JPEG)\n\n\n  The final graph of $y=h(x)$ is shown below\n  ![SkillUpp Image](https://assets.revisionvillage.com/public/question/c12c7015-df65-4beb-b764-cc77e7025623/images/36471d45-1f48-4d32-ac28-33498e303129/AA1279-a3.JPEG)\n\n\n\n  $$\n  \\begin{align*}\n      \\answer{\\text{Correct points at }(-2, -4)\\text{ and }(-6,0)}\\tag*{\\textbf{A1}}\\\\[6pt]\n       \\answer{\\text{Correct transformation(s)}}\\tag*{\\textbf{A1}}\n  \\end{align*}\n  $$\n\n- First, let's look at the section of the graph $0\\leq x \\leq 2$.\n  We can use the properties of the transformation $[f(x)]^2$ to identify some key points.\n  We know that if $f(x)=0$ then $[f(x)]^2=0$.\n  We also know that if $f(x)=1$ then $[f(x)]^2=1$.\n  It is important to also realise that if $-1<f(x)<1$ then $[f(x)]^2<f(x)$.\n  Therefore between $0<x<1$ then $[f(x)]^2<f(x)$.\n  Using the end point of the first part of the curve we can see that $[f(2)]^2=4$.\n  Using the key points $(0,0)$, $(1,1)$ and $(2,4)$ we can sketch the transformed curve, shown in $\\textcolor{red}{\\text{red}}$\n  ![SkillUpp Image](https://assets.revisionvillage.com/public/question/c12c7015-df65-4beb-b764-cc77e7025623/images/1850a5f9-cc57-42c9-aced-4f5076f93f70/AA1279-a4.JPEG)\n\n\n  Now, let's look at the section of the graph $2\\leq x \\leq 6$.\n  We know the second section will start at $(2,4)$ and finish at $(6,0)$.\n  Using the property if $f(x)=1$ then $[f(x)]^2=1$ we know the curve will intersect the original function at $f(x)=1$.\n  Which we can see is at $(4,1)$.\n  It is important to clearly show on the graph that $[f(x)]^2<f(x)$ when $0<f(x)<1$.\n  With this in mind, using the key points $(2,4)$, $(1,4)$ and $(6,0)$ we can sketch the second part, shown in $\\textcolor{blue}{\\text{blue}}$\n  ![SkillUpp Image](https://assets.revisionvillage.com/public/question/c12c7015-df65-4beb-b764-cc77e7025623/images/df6ea7d7-12e8-4c02-9e9e-59b469c720e1/AA1279-a5.JPEG)\n\n\n  The final graph of $y=[f(x)]^2$ is shown below\n  ![SkillUpp Image](https://assets.revisionvillage.com/public/question/c12c7015-df65-4beb-b764-cc77e7025623/images/d8f9fbfb-5406-4219-9359-a6a3e373e1ae/AA1279-a6.JPEG)\n\n\n\n  $$\n  \\begin{align*}\n      &\\answer{\\text{Correct shape}}\\tag*{\\textbf{A1}}\\\\[6pt]\n      &\\answer{\\text{$f(x)=[f(x)]^2$ when $f(x)=0,1$}}\\tag*{\\textbf{A1}}\\\\[6pt]\n      &\\answer{\\text{$[f(x)]^2$} \\text{ is less than } f(x) \\text{ when } 0<f(x)<1}\\tag*{\\textbf{A1}}\n  \\end{align*}\n  $$\n\n- Let's start by drawing the vertical asymptotes.\n  They will occur at the $x$-intercepts of $f(x)$ which are $x=0$ and $x=6$. Shown below as the dotted red vertical lines\n  ![SkillUpp Image](https://assets.revisionvillage.com/public/question/c12c7015-df65-4beb-b764-cc77e7025623/images/e1ad22e1-6249-4f31-ba13-092dd647afbb/AA1279-a7.JPEG)\n\n\n  Let's consider the key point $(2,2)$, after the transformation this point will become $(2,\\tfrac{1}{2})$.\n  Considering the asymptotes, we can see that as $x\\rightarrow 0$ and $x\\rightarrow 6$ then $f(x)\\rightarrow 0$ (from the positive direction) therefore $\\frac{1}{f(x)}\\rightarrow \\infty^+$.\n  Hence we get the graph below in $\\textcolor{blue}{\\text{blue}}$.\n  ![SkillUpp Image](https://assets.revisionvillage.com/public/question/c12c7015-df65-4beb-b764-cc77e7025623/images/4d398d26-b01f-4f29-993f-5ab558c1e147/AA1279-a8.JPEG)\n\n\n  The final graph of $y=\\frac{1}{f(x)}$ is shown below\n  ![SkillUpp Image](https://assets.revisionvillage.com/public/question/c12c7015-df65-4beb-b764-cc77e7025623/images/c11d79ea-8c87-4a3e-9c0e-bcd8cf6583d1/AA1279-a9.JPEG)\n\n\n\n  $$\n  \\begin{align*}\n  &\\answer{\\text{Correct asymptotes}}\\tag*{\\textbf{A1}}\\\\[6pt]\n  &\\answer{\\text{Correct shape}}\\tag*{\\textbf{A1}}\\\\[6pt]\n  &\\answer{\\text{Correct minimum point at } (2,\\tfrac{1}{2})}\\tag*{\\textbf{A1}}\n  \\end{align*}\n  $$\n\n",
