    content:
      'The function $f$ is defined by $f(x) = 1+ \\dfrac{4x}{x+3}$, for\n$x \\neq -3$.\n\n- Sketch the graph of $y = f(x)$, indicating clearly any asymptotes\nand\npoints of intersection with the $x$ and $y$ axes. <span class="marks">[4]</span>\n\n- Find an expression for $f^{-1}$. <span class="marks">[4]</span>\n\n- Find all values of $x$ for which $f(x) = f^{-1}(x)$. <span class="marks">[3]</span>\n\n- Solve the inequality $|f(x)| < 2$. <span class="marks">[4]</span>\n\n- Solve the inequality $f(|x|) < 2$. <span class="marks">[2]</span>\n\n',
    markScheme:
      '\n- If we solve the equation $f(x) = 0$ for $x$, we get\n\n  $$\n  \\begin{aligned}\n  1+ \\dfrac{4x}{x+3} &= 0 \\\\[6pt]\n  \\dfrac{5x+3}{x+3} &= 0 \\\\[11pt]\n  5x + 3 &= 0 \\\\[10pt]\n  x &= -\\dfrac{3}{5} \\hspace{2.1em} \\\\\n  \\end{aligned}\n  $$\n\n  Hence the point\nP$(-3/5,0)$ is the $x$-intercept of the graph of $y = f(x)$.\n  Evaluating $y = f(x)$ for $x = 0$, we obtain\n\n  $$\n  \\begin{aligned}\n  \\hspace{2em} y &= f(0) \\\\[6pt]\n  &= 1\\end{aligned}\n  $$\n\n  Hence the point Q$(0,1)$ is the $y$-intercept of\nthe graph of $y = f(x)$.\n  We have\n\n  $$\n  \\begin{aligned}\n  \\lim_{x \\rightarrow\\pm\\infty} f(x) &= 1 + \\dfrac{4}{1} \\hspace{3.7em} \\\\[6pt]\n  &= 5\\end{aligned}\n  $$\n\n  Hence the line $y = 5$ is a horizontal asymptote\nof the graph of $y = f(x)$.\n  The denominator of $f$ is zero when $x = -3$. Hence the line\n$x = -3$\nis a vertical asymptote of the graph of $y = f(x)$.\n  If we sketch of the graph of $y = f(x)$, we have\n  ![SkillUpp Image](https://assets.revisionvillage.com/public/question/b02f9456-fc87-4d72-8046-b8ad6f17fd88/images/80e5d1bc-25e1-48da-ad0b-cf11c4df076c/a4ee5024679811f4302b4cf52d17f68170c60827.svg)\n\n\n- If we solve the equation $(f\\circ f^{-1})(x) = x$ for\n$y = f^{-1}(x)$, we find\n\n  $$\n  \\begin{aligned}\n  f(f^{-1}(x)) &= x \\hspace{3.7em}  \\\\[8pt]\n  f\\left(y\\right) &= x\\end{aligned}\n  $$\n\n\n  $$\n  \\begin{aligned}\n  \\hspace{1.7em} 1+ \\dfrac{4y}{y+3} &= x \\\\[6pt]\n  \\dfrac{5y+3}{y+3} &= x \\\\[10pt]\n  5y+3 &= xy+3x \\\\[16pt]\n  (5-x)y &= 3x-3 \\\\[10pt]\n  y &= \\dfrac{3x-3}{5-x} \\\\\n  \\end{aligned}\n  $$\n\n  Hence an expression for\n$f^{-1}$ is\n$\\answer{f^{-1}(x) = \\dfrac{3x-3}{5-x}}$\n- If we solve the equation $f(x) = f^{-1}(x)$ for $x$, we get\n\n  $$\n  \\begin{aligned}\n  f(x) &= f^{-1}(x) \\\\[9pt]\n  1 + \\dfrac{4x}{x+3} &= \\dfrac{3x-3}{5-x} \\\\[6pt]\n  \\dfrac{5x+3}{x+3} &= \\dfrac{3x-3}{5-x} \\\\[10pt]\n  (5x+3)(5-x) &= (3x-3)(x+3) \\\\[12pt]\n  \\hspace{1.6em} 25x - 5x^2 + 15 -3x &= 3x^2 + 9x -3x - 9 \\\\[12pt]\n  -8x^2 + 16x + 24 &= 0\\end{aligned}\n  $$\n\n\n  $$\n  \\begin{aligned}\n  x^2 - 2x - 3 &= 0 \\\\[12pt]\n  (x+1)(x-3) &= 0 \\hspace{4em} \\\\\n  \\end{aligned}\n  $$\n\n\n  $$\n  \\hspace{3.6em} \\answer{x = -1,\\hspace{0.25em}3}\n  $$\n\n- We have\n\n  $$\n  \\begin{aligned}\n  \n  \\hspace{8.1em} \\begin{array}{rcccl}\n  && |f(x)| &<& 2 \\\\[13pt]\n  -2 &<& f(x) &<& 2 \\\\[12pt]\n  f^{-1}(-2) &<& x &<& f^{-1}(2) \\hspace{2em} [\\text{since $f^{-1}(f(x)) = x$}]\n  \\end{array}\\end{aligned}\n  $$\n\n  Evaluating $y = f^{-1}(x)$ for $x = -2$,\nwe get\n\n  $$\n  \\begin{aligned}\n  \\hspace{2.4em} f^{-1}(-2) &= \\dfrac{3(-2)-3}{5-(-2)} \\\\[3pt]\n  &= -\\dfrac{9}{7} \\\\\n  \\end{aligned}\n  $$\n\n  Evaluating $y = f^{-1}(x)$ for\n$x = 2$, we obtain\n\n  $$\n  \\begin{aligned}\n  \\hspace{3.2em} f^{-1}(2) &= \\dfrac{3(2)-3}{5-2}  \\hspace{0.8em} \\\\[8pt]\n  &= 1 \\\\\n  \\end{aligned}\n  $$\n\n  Hence the set of solutions to the inequality\n$|f(x)| < 2$ is\n$\\answer{-\\frac{9}{7}<x<1}$\n- If we solve the inequality $f(|x|) < 2$ for $|x|$, we get\n\n  $$\n  \\begin{aligned}\n  \\hspace{0.5em} 1+ \\dfrac{4|x|}{|x|+3} &< 2 \\\\[5pt]\n  \\dfrac{4|x|}{|x|+3} &< 1 \\\\[10pt]\n  4|x| &< |x|+3 \\\\[16pt]\n  3|x| &< 3 \\\\[16pt]\n  |x| &< 1 \\\\\n  \\end{aligned}\n  $$\n\n  Hence the set of solutions to the\ninequality $f(|x|) < 2$ is\n$\\answer{-1<x<1}$\n',
