      'Consider the function $f(x)=5xe^x+1$.\nThe function has a single point of inflexion at $A$.\n\n- Show that the point of inflexion  of $f(x)$ occurs when $x=-2$. <span class="marks">[3]</span>\n\n- Sketch $f(x)$ on the grid below, label point $A$ and any asymptotes.<span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n  ![SkillUpp Image](https://assets.revisionvillage.com/public/question/04090a8e-6d70-4a75-a5e4-341287b09a7d/images/0957c93a-b030-4309-ad29-4635f77a12cf/AA1156_q.JPEG)\n\n\n- The line $g(x)=mx+c$ passes through $A$ for all values of $m$ and $c$.\n  \n  - Evaluate $m$ when $g(x)$ is tangent to $f(x)$ at point $A$.\n  - Hence find the range of values of $m$ for which $f(x)=g(x)$ has exactly $3$ solutions. <span class="marks">[4]</span>\n\n\n',
    markScheme:
      "\n- Recognise that inflexion points occur when $f''(x)=0$.\n\n  $$\n  \\begin{align*}\n      \\textcolor{white}{hack}\\tag*{\\textbf{M1}}\n  \\end{align*}\n  $$\n\n  Use the product rule to differentiate $f(x)$.\n\n  $$\n  \\begin{align*}\n      f'(x)&=(5x)'e^x+5x(e^x)'\\\\[6pt]\n      &=5e^x+5xe^x\n  \\end{align*}\n  $$\n\n  Now we use a similar method to find $f''(x)$\n\n  $$\n  \\begin{align*}\n      f''(x)&=5e^x+5e^x+5xe^x\\\\[6pt]\n      &=10e^x+5xe^x\\tag*{\\textbf{A1}}\n  \\end{align*}\n  $$\n\n  Now we solve the equation $f''(x)=0$\n\n  $$\n  \\begin{align*}\n      0&=10e^x+5xe^x\\\\[6pt]\n      &=5e^x(2+x) \\tag*{\\textbf{A1}}\\\\[6pt]\n      2+x&=0\\\\[6pt]\n      &\\hspace{-0.5em}\\tcbhighmath{x=-2} \\hspace{2em} \\text{...as required.}\n  \\end{align*}\n  $$\n\n- Here is the sketch of $f(x)$ with the required elements highlighted\n  ![SkillUpp Image](https://assets.revisionvillage.com/public/question/04090a8e-6d70-4a75-a5e4-341287b09a7d/images/938f99b3-82b2-4be3-8842-3773b2f2b666/AA1156_s0.JPEG)\n\n\n\n  $$\n  \\begin{align*}\n      \\textcolor{white}{hack}\\tag*{\\textbf{A1}}\n  \\end{align*}\n  $$\n\n- \n  - Recognise that $m=f'(-2)$.\n    Using the G.D.C. we can find $m$\n\n    $$\n    \\begin{align*}\n        f'(-2)&=-0.6767...\\\\[6pt]\n        &\\hspace{-0.8em}\\tcbhighmath{m=-0.677} \\tag*{\\textbf{A1}}\n    \\end{align*}\n    $$\n\n  - The tangent at $A$ intersects $f(x)$ at one point.\n    ![SkillUpp Image](https://assets.revisionvillage.com/public/question/04090a8e-6d70-4a75-a5e4-341287b09a7d/images/61f12b76-8fd9-4fec-a868-4affacf96f18/AA1156_s1.JPEG)\n\n\n    Therefore when $m=-0.6767...$ there is one solution for $f(x)=g(x)$.\n    As $m$ approaches $0$ we see below that there are $3$ solutions to $f(x)=g(x)$.\n    ![SkillUpp Image](https://assets.revisionvillage.com/public/question/04090a8e-6d70-4a75-a5e4-341287b09a7d/images/58cf6bf2-796c-49e5-845f-715535e686dc/AA1156_s2.JPEG)\n\n\n    When $m=0$ $g(x)$ is parallel to the asymptote, we can see below that there are $2$ solutions to $f(x)=g(x)$.\n    ![SkillUpp Image](https://assets.revisionvillage.com/public/question/04090a8e-6d70-4a75-a5e4-341287b09a7d/images/f5ae73cb-47b3-4254-8cf5-b5fd67a36f92/AA1156_s3.JPEG)\n\n\n    Therefore there are $3$ solutions to $f(x)=g(x)$ when $\\answer{-0.677<m<0}$\n    A1A1 Correct end points \nA1 $\\hspace{1.5em}$Correct inequality signs\n\n",
