    title: 'Question 51',
    content:
      'The function $f$ is defined by $f(x) = e^{2x}-4e^x+2$, for\n$x \\in \\mathbb{R}$, $x \\leq a$, where $a \\in \\mathbb{R}$.\nPart of the graph of $y = f(x)$ is shown in the following diagram.\n![SkillUpp Image](https://assets.revisionvillage.com/public/question/4c5c56b3-ccff-4218-8eeb-ed43662a5361/images/6b8a627c-1929-4344-ac27-a9f1d77bd6ab/dc14321f698d30780f4ecaf20c082a22181a9565.svg)\n\n\n\n- Find the largest value of $a$ such that $f$ has an inverse function.\n<span class="marks">[3]</span>\n\n- For this value of $a$, find an expression for $f^{-1}(x)$, stating\nits domain. <span class="marks">[5]</span>\n\n',
    markScheme:
      "\n- From the diagram, we see that the $x$-coordinate of the local\nminimum point on the graph of $y = f(x)$ is the largest value of $a$\nsuch that $f$ has an inverse function.\n  We have\n\n  $$\n  \\begin{aligned}\n  f'(x) &= \\dfrac{\\mathrm{d}}{\\mathrm{d}x}\\big[e^{2x}-4e^x+2\\big] \\\\[6pt]\n  &= 2e^{2x}-4e^x \\\\[9pt]\n  &= \\big[2e^x\\big]\\big[e^x - 2\\big]\\end{aligned}\n  $$\n\n  If we solve the equation $f'(x) = 0$ for $x$, we get\n\n  $$\n  \\begin{aligned}\n  \\big[2e^x\\big]\\big[e^x - 2\\big] &= 0 \\hspace{5.2em} \\\\[6pt]\n  e^x - 2 &= 0 \\\\[7pt]\n  e^x &= 2 \\\\[7pt]\n  x &= \\ln 2\\end{aligned}\n  $$\n\n  Hence we find\n$\\answer{a = \\ln 2}$\n- If we solve the equation $(f\\circ f^{-1})(x) = x$ for\n$y =  f^{-1}(x)$, we obtain\n\n  $$\n  \\begin{aligned}\n  f(f^{-1}(x)) &= x \\hspace{3em} [\\text{where $-2 \\leq x < 2$}] \\\\[9pt]\n  f(y) &= x \\hspace{3em} [\\text{where $y \\leq \\ln 2$}] \\\\[7pt]\n  e^{2y}-4e^y+2 &= x \\\\[7pt]\n  \\big[(e^y)^2-4e^y\\big]+2 &= x \\\\[7pt]\n  \\hspace{7.1em} \\big[(e^y-2)^2 - 4\\big]+2 &= x \\hspace{3em} [\\text{by completing the square}] \\\\[7pt]\n  (e^y-2)^2 &= x+2 \\\\[7pt]\n  e^y-2 &= \\pm\\sqrt{x+2} \\\\[7pt]\n  e^y-2 &= -\\sqrt{x+2} \\hspace{3em} [\\text{since $y \\leq \\ln 2$}] \\\\[7pt]\n  e^y &= 2-\\sqrt{x+2} \\\\[7pt]\n  y &= \\ln (2-\\sqrt{x+2})\\end{aligned}\n  $$\n\n  Hence we find\n$\\answer{f^{-1}(x) = \\ln (2-\\sqrt{x+2}), \\text{ for } x \\in \\mathbb{R}, -2 \\leq x < 2}$\n",
    paper: 'PAPER1',
    difficulty: 'HARD',
