    title: 'Question 52',
    content:
      'This question asks you to investigate some properties of even and odd functions.\nConsider the functions $f_1(x)=\\dfrac{5}{x^3}$ and $f_2(x)=3x^2+8$.\n\n- Determine whether:\n  \n  - The function $f_1(x)$ is an even function or an odd function,\n  - The function $f_2(x)$ is an even function or an odd function.<span class="marks">[4]</span>\n\n\n\nSuppose $g(x)$ is a function with domain $\\mathbb{R}$ and let $h$ and $j$ be the functions\n\n$$\n\\begin{align*}\n  h(x)=\\dfrac{g(x)+g(-x)}{2},\\quad j(x)=\\dfrac{g(x)-g(-x)}{2}\\\\[-12pt]  \n\\end{align*}\n$$\n\n\n- \n  - Show that $g(x)=h(x)+j(x).$\n  - Hence, show that $g(x)$ is the sum of an even and an odd function.<span class="marks">[4]</span>\n\n\n- Using the results from part (b), find the even part and the odd part of\n\n$g(x)=x^4+4x^3+5x^2-2x$<span class="marks">[3]</span>\n\nLet $f(x)$ be a function that is differentiable for all $x \\in \\mathbb{R}.$\n\n- Show that:\n  \n  - if $f(x)$ is an even function, then $f\'(x)$ is an odd function\n  - if $f(x)$ is an odd function, then $f\'(x)$ is an even function.<span class="marks">[4]</span>\n\n\n- Show that if $f(x)$ is an even function defined and differentiable at $x=0,$ then:\n  \n  - $f\'(0)=0$,\n  - $f^{2k+1}(0)=0$ for $k \\in \\mathbb{Z}^+$,\n  - its Maclaurin series expansion contains only even powers of $x$.<span class="marks">[5]</span>\n\n\n- Show that if $f(x)$ is an odd function, then its Maclaurin series expansion contains only odd powers of $x.$ <span class="marks">[5]</span>\n\n',
    markScheme:
      "\n- \n  - Evaluating $f_1$ at $-x$, we get\n\n    $$\n    \\begin{align*}\n    f_1(-x) & =\\dfrac{5}{(-x)^3} \\\\[8pt]\n    &=-\\dfrac{5}{x^3}\\\\[8pt]\n    &= -f_1(x) \\\\[-10pt]\n    \\end{align*}\n    $$\n\n    Since $f_1(-x)=-f_1(x)$, $\\answer{\\text{the function } f_1(x) \\text{ is an odd function.}}$\n  - Evaluating $f_2$ at $-x$, we get\n\n    $$\n    \\begin{align*}\n    f_2(-x) &=3(-x)^2+8 \\\\[8pt]\n    &=3x^2+8\\\\[8pt]\n    &= f_2(x) \\\\[-10pt]\n    \\end{align*}\n    $$\n\n    Since $f_2(-x)=f_2(x),$ $\\answer{\\text{the function } f_2(x) \\text{ is an even function.}}$\n\n- \n  - Taking the sum of $h$ and $j$, we obtain\n\n    $$\n    \\begin{align*}\n    h(x)+j(x)&=\\dfrac{g(x)+g(-x)}{2}+\\dfrac{g(x)-g(-x)}{2}\\\\[12pt]\n    &=\\dfrac{2g(x)}{2}\\\\[12pt]\n    &\\hspace{-5.2em}\\tcbhighmath{h(x)+j(x) = g(x)}\n    \\end{align*}\n    $$\n\n  - Evaluating $h$ at $-x$, we get\n\n    $$\n    \\begin{align*}\n    h(-x)&=\\dfrac{g(-x)+g(x)}{2}\\\\[12pt]\n    &= \\dfrac{g(x)+g(-x)}{2} \\\\[12pt]\n    &=h(x)\\\\[-11pt]\n    \\end{align*}\n    $$\n\n    Therefore, $h(x)$ is an even function.\n    Now, evaluating $j$ at $-x$, we get\n\n    $$\n    \\begin{align*}\n    j(-x)&=\\dfrac{g(-x)-g(x)}{2}\\\\[12pt]\n    &=-\\dfrac{g(x)-g(-x)}{2}\\\\[12pt]\n    &=-j(x)\\\\[-11pt]\n    \\end{align*}\n    $$\n\n    Therefore, $j(x)$ is an odd function.\n    Since $g(x)=h(x)+j(x)$, any function $g(x)$ can be written as the sum of an even function and an odd function.\n\n- Evaluating $g$ at $-x$, we get\n\n  $$\n  \\begin{align*}\n  g(-x)&=(-x)^4+4(-x)^3+5(-x)^2-2(-x)\\\\[12pt]\n  &=x^4-4x^3+5x^2+2x\n  \\end{align*}\n  $$\n\n  From part (b), the even part of $g(x)$ is $h(x)$.\n\n  $$\n  \\begin{align*}\n  h(x)&=\\dfrac{g(x)+g(-x)}{2} \\\\[12pt]\n  &=\\dfrac{(x^4+4x^3+5x^2-2x)+(x^4-4x^3+5x^2+2x)}{2}\\\\[12pt]\n  &=\\dfrac{2x^4+10x^2}{2}\\\\[12pt]\n  &\\hspace{0.275em}\\tcbhighmath{= x^4+5x^2}\n  \\end{align*}\n  $$\n\n  The odd part of $g(x)$ is $j(x)$.\n\n  $$\n  \\begin{align*}\n  j(x)&=\\dfrac{g(x)-g(-x)}{2}\\\\[12pt]\n  &=\\dfrac{(x^4+4x^3+5x^2-2x)-(x^4-4x^3+5x^2+2x)}{2}\\\\[12pt]\n  &=\\dfrac{8x^3-4x}{2}\\\\[12pt]    \n  &\\hspace{0.275em}\\tcbhighmath{=4x^3-2x }\n  \\end{align*}\n  $$\n\n- \n  - Let's suppose that $f(x)$ is an even function. Thus, we have\n\n    $$\n    \\begin{align*}\n    f(-x) &= f(x) \\\\[12pt]\n    -f'(-x) &= f'(x)\\\\[12pt]\n    f'(-x) &= -f'(x)\\\\[-9pt]\n    \\end{align*}\n    $$\n\n    Therefore,$\\,\\,\\answer{\\text{ $f'(x)$ is an odd function.}}$\n  - Let's suppose that $f(x)$ is an odd function. Thus, we have\n\n    $$\n    \\begin{align*}\n    f(-x) &= -f(x) \\\\[12pt]\n    -f'(-x)&=-f'(x)\\\\[12pt]\n    f'(-x) &= f'(x)\\\\[-9pt]\n    \\end{align*}\n    $$\n\n    Therefore, $\\,\\answer{\\text{ $f'(x)$ is an even function.}}$\n\n- \n  - By part (d), if $f(x)$ is an even function then $f'(x)$ is an odd function. We get\n\n    $$\n    \\begin{align*}\n    f'(-0)&=-f'(0)\\\\[12pt]\n    f'(0) &=-f'(0)\\\\[12pt]\n    2f'(0) &= 0 \\\\[12pt]\n    &\\hspace{-2.4em}\\tcbhighmath{f'(0) = 0}\n    \\end{align*}\n    $$\n\n  - Using part (d) (i), $f(x)$ even $\\Rightarrow f'(x)$ odd.\n    Using part (d) (ii), $f'(x)$ odd $\\Rightarrow f''(x)$ even.\n    By iteration, we have that every odd derivative is an odd function and every even derivative is an even function. That is, $f^{2k+1}(x)$ is odd and $f^{2k}(x)$ is even for $k \\in \\mathbb{Z}^+$. Hence,\n\n    $$\n    \\begin{align*}\n    f^{2k+1}(-x)&=-f^{2k+1}(x)\\\\[12pt]\n    f^{2k+1}(-0)&=-f^{2k+1}(0)\\\\[12pt]\n    f^{2k+1}(0) &=-f^{2k+1}(0)\\\\[12pt]\n    2f^{2k+1}(0) &= 0 \\\\[12pt]\n    &\\hspace{-3.85em}\\tcbhighmath{f^{2k+1}(0) = 0}\n    \\end{align*}\n    $$\n\n  - The Maclaurin series expansion of $f(x)$ is\n\n    $$\n    \\begin{align*}\n    f(x)=f(0)+xf'(0)+\\dfrac{x^2}{2!}f''(0)+\\dfrac{x^3}{3!}f^{(3)}(0)+\\cdots\n    \\end{align*}\n    $$\n\n    From part (ii), $f'(0)=0$ and $f^{2k+1}(0)=0$ for $k \\in \\mathbb{Z}^+$, which means that\n    The only non-zero terms remaining in the Maclaurin series expansion are those of the form $\\dfrac{x^{2k}}{(2k)!}f^{2k}(0)$, those with even powers of $x$, including the constant term.\n\n- By part (d), if $f(x)$ is an odd function then $f'(x)$ is an even function and $f''(x)$ is an odd function. Using parts (d) (i) and (ii), by iteration, every even derivative is an odd function.\n  We can say that $f^{2k}(x)$ is an odd function for $k \\in \\mathbb{Z}^+$. Thus, we have\n\n  $$\n  \\begin{align*}\n  f^{2k}(-x) &= -f^{2k}(x) \\\\[12pt]\n  f^{2k}(-0)&=-f^{2k}(0)\\\\[12pt]\n  f^{2k}(0)&=-f^{2k}(0)\\\\[12pt]\n  2f^{2k}(0) &= 0 \\\\[12pt]\n  f^{2k}(0) &= 0\n  \\end{align*}\n  $$\n\n  The Maclaurin series expansion of $f(x)$ is\n\n  $$\n  \\begin{align*}\n  f(x)=f(0)+xf'(0)+\\dfrac{x^2}{2!}f''(0)+\\dfrac{x^3}{3!}f^{(3)}(0)+\\cdots\n  \\end{align*}\n  $$\n\n  Therefore the terms with even powers in the Maclaurin series of $f(x)$ vanish and the Maclaurin series of $f(x)$ contains only terms with odd powers of $x$.\n",
