    title: 'Question 21',
    content:
      'The quadratic equation $x^2 - kx + (k-1) = 0$ has roots $\\alpha$ and\n$\\beta$. Without solving the equation, find the possible values of the\nreal number $k$ given that $\\alpha^2 + \\beta^2 = 17$.',
    markScheme:
      "Using Vieta's formulas, we have\n\n$$\n\\begin{aligned}\n\\alpha+\\beta &=-\\dfrac{a_1}{a_2} \\\\[4pt]\n&= -\\dfrac{(-k)}{1} \\\\[12pt]\n&= k\\end{aligned}\n$$\n\nand\n\n$$\n\\begin{aligned}\n\\hspace{2.9em} \\alpha\\beta &= (-1)^2\\bigg[\\dfrac{a_0}{a_2}\\bigg] \\\\[4pt]\n&= \\dfrac{k-1}{1} \\\\[12pt]\n&= k-1\\end{aligned}\n$$\n\nHence we get\n\n$$\n\\begin{aligned}(\\alpha + \\beta)^2  &= k^2 \\\\[6pt]\\hspace{5.8em} \\alpha^2 + \\beta^2 + 2\\alpha\\beta &= k^2 \\\\[6pt]17 + 2(k - 1)  &=  k^2 \\hspace{3em} [\\text{since } \\alpha^2 + \\beta^2 = 17] \\\\[6pt]2k + 15  &=  k^2 \\\\[6pt]0 &= k^2 - 2k - 15 \\\\[7pt]0 &= (k+3)(k-5)\\end{aligned}\n$$\n\n\n$$\n\\hspace{1.4em} \\answer{k = -3,\\hspace{0.25em}5}\n$$\n",
    paper: 'PAPER1',
    difficulty: 'EASY',
    calculator: false,
    sort: 1,
    maxMark: '5',
