    content:
      'Consider the function $\\displaystyle f(x)=\\frac{\\cos(mx)-\\cos(nx)}{x^2}$ where $m,n \\in \\mathbb{R}$.\nThe function has a maximum value of $f_{\\text{max}}$ and it is known that $\\displaystyle f_{\\text{max}}= \\lim_{x \\to 0} f(x)$.\n\n- Show that $\\displaystyle f_{\\text{max}}=\\frac{n^2-m^2}{2}$. <span class="marks">[6]</span>  \n\nIt is now known that $m>0$ and $n=4\\sqrt{m}$.\n\n- Hence, using these conditions find the largest possible value of $f_{\\text{max}}$. <span class="marks">[2]</span>  \n',
    markScheme:
      "\n- To find $f_{\\text{max}}$ we need to evaluate $f(x)$ as $x \\rightarrow 0$.\n  Hence we can write\n\n  $$\n  \\begin{align*}\n      f_{\\text{max}}&=\\lim_{x \\to 0} \\left(\\frac{\\cos(mx)-\\cos(nx)}{x^2}\\right)\n  \\end{align*}\n  $$\n\n  We can begin by attempting to evaluate the limit using direct substitution of $x=0$, recall $\\cos{0}=1$.\n\n  $$\n  \\begin{align*}\n      f_{\\text{max}}&= \\frac{\\cos(0)-\\cos(0)}{(0)^2}\\tag*{\\textbf{(M1)}}\\\\[12pt]\n      &= \\frac{1-1}{(0)^2}\\\\[12pt]\n      &=\\frac{0}{0}\n  \\end{align*}\n  $$\n\n  This is an indeterminate form. Hence we can use L'Hpital's Rule to attempt to find the limit.\n\n  $$\n  \\begin{align*}\n       \\tag*{\\textbf{R1}}\n  \\end{align*}\n  $$\n\n  Using the standard derivative for cosine and the power rule we can differentiate the numerator and denominator to get\n\n  $$\n  \\begin{align*}\n      f_{\\text{max}}&=\\lim_{x \\to 0} \\left(\\frac{-m\\sin(mx)-(-n\\sin(nx))}{2x}\\right)\\tag*{\\textbf{\\textcolor{black}{M1}}}\\\\[12pt]\n      &=\\lim_{x \\to 0} \\left(\\frac{-m\\sin(mx)+n\\sin(nx)}{2x}\\right)\n  \\end{align*}\n  $$\n\n  Again we can attempt to evaluate the limit by direct substitution of $x=0$\n\n  $$\n   \\begin{align*}\n      f_{\\text{max}}&=\\lim_{x \\to 0} \\left(\\frac{-m\\sin(0)+n\\sin(0))}{2(0)}\\right)\\\\[12pt]\n      &=\\frac{0}{0}\\tag*{\\textbf{\\textcolor{black}{A1}}}\n  \\end{align*}\n  $$\n\n  Again we have an indeterminate form. Let's try L'Hpital's Rule one more time.\n\n  $$\n   \\begin{align*}\n      f_{\\text{max}}&=\\lim_{x \\to 0} \\left(\\frac{-m^2\\cos(mx)+n^2\\cos(nx)}{2}\\right)\\tag*{\\textbf{\\textcolor{black}{A1}}}\n  \\end{align*}\n  $$\n\n  As $\\cos{0}=1$ we get\n\n  $$\n  \\begin{align*}\n       \\tag*{\\textbf{M1}}\n  \\end{align*}\n  $$\n\n\n  $$\n  \\begin{align*}\n      &=\\frac{-m^2+n^2}{2}\\\\[12pt]\n      &=\\answer{\\dfrac{n^2-m^2}{2}} \\hspace{2em}\\text{...as required}\n  \\end{align*}\n  $$\n\n- We can take the result from part (b) and replace $n$ with $4\\sqrt{m}$, this gives $f_{\\text{max}}$ in terms of $m$\n\n  $$\n  \\begin{align*}\n      f_{\\text{max}}&=\\frac{(4\\sqrt{m})^2-m^2}{2}\n  \\end{align*}\n  $$\n\n  This is a quadratic function in $m$.\n  By completing the square we can write $f_\\text{max}$ in vertex form and find the coordinates of the maximum point.\n  Note, although we are told to look for a maximum value we can also see that as the coefficient of $m^2$ is negative then the parabola will be concave down hence the vertex will be a maximum point.\n  When completing the square it is often easier to work with a positive squared term hence we will factorise by $-\\tfrac{1}{2}$ which gives\n\n  $$\n  \\begin{align*}\n      f_{\\text{max}}&=-\\frac{1}{2}(m^2-16m)\n  \\end{align*}\n  $$\n\n  Now we can complete the square\n\n  $$\n  \\begin{align*}\n      &=-\\frac{1}{2}\\left[(m-8)^2-64\\right]\\tag*{\\textbf{\\textcolor{black}{(M1)}}}\\\\[6pt]\n      &=-\\frac{1}{2}(m-8)^2+32\n  \\end{align*}\n  $$\n\n  Hence the largest value of $f_\\text{max}$ is $\\answer{32}$\n\n  $$\n  \\begin{align*}\n       \\tag*{\\textbf{A1}}\n  \\end{align*}\n  $$\n\n",
