    title: 'Question 44',
    content:
      'Consider the quadratic polynomial $p(x)=2kx^2 + 15kx + 3k + 6$, where $k\\in\\mathbb{R}$.\n\n- Find an expression for the product of the roots of $p(x)$ in terms of $k$. <span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n- Find the values of $k$ for which $p(x)$ has two distinct negative real roots. <span class="marks">[5]</span>\n\n',
    markScheme:
      '\n- Let $\\alpha$ and $\\beta$ be the two roots of $p(x)$. The product of the roots of a polynomial is given by\n  $\\dfrac{(-1)^na_0}{a_n}$\n  In this case we have $n=2$, $a_0=3k+6$ and $a_n=2k$. Therefore\n\n  $$\n  \\begin{align*}\n  \\alpha\\beta &= \\dfrac{(-1)^2(3k+6)}{2k} \\\\[10pt]\n  &\\hspace{-1.2em}\\tcbhighmath{\\alpha\\beta = \\dfrac{3k+6}{2k}} \n  \\end{align*}\n  $$\n\n- Using the quadratic formula, we can find an expression for the roots of the polynomial:\n\n  $$\n  \\begin{align*}\n  x &= \\dfrac{-15k \\pm \\sqrt{(15k)^2 - 4(2k)(3k+6)}}{4k} \\\\[10pt]\n  &= \\dfrac{-15}{4} \\pm \\dfrac{\\sqrt{201k^2 - 48k}}{4k}\n  \\end{align*}\n  $$\n\n  This implies that there must be at least one negative root, and it is therefore not possible to have two positive roots.\n  If the product of the roots is positive, then the polynomial will have two negative roots.\n  Using G.D.C. to plot $\\alpha\\beta$ as a function of $k$, we get\n  ![SkillUpp Image](https://assets.revisionvillage.com/public/question/fb00108c-b3ff-42f3-aeed-bd72cebd43f7/images/8029e1d2-dfda-41d0-8f32-2a8f0cdb3a70/AA932a.PNG)\n\n\n  Hence, we can see that the product $\\alpha\\beta$ is greater than zero when $k<-2$ and when $k>0$. Therefore, for values of $k$ in these intervals, the polynomial has two negative roots.\n  For both roots to be distinct and real, the discriminant must be greater than zero. We have\n\n  $$\n  \\begin{align*}\n  b^2 - 4ac &> 0 \\\\[10pt]\n  201k^2 - 48k &> 0 \\\\[10pt]\n  k(201k - 48) &> 0 \\\\[10pt]\n  k &<0 \\text{ , } k > \\dfrac{48}{201}\n  \\end{align*}\n  $$\n\n  For the roots to be distinct, real, and both negative, we must have $k<-2$ or $k>\\dfrac{48}{201}$.\n  Hence, $p(x)$ has two distinct negative real roots for $\\answer{k<-2 \\text{ and } k>\\dfrac{48}{201}}$\n',
