    content:
      'This question asks you to explore the sequence defined by\n\n$$\nu_n=\\dfrac{\\sqrt{3}}{6}(\\alpha^n-\\beta^n)\n$$\n\nwhere $\\alpha$ and $\\beta$\nare the roots of the quadratic equation $x^2-4x+1=0, \\, \\alpha > \\beta$\nand $n \\in \\mathbb{Z}^+$.\n\n- Find the value of $\\alpha$ and the value of $\\beta$. Give your answers in the form $a \\pm \\sqrt{b}$, where $a,b \\in \\mathbb{Z^+}$.<span class="marks">[3]</span>\n\n- Hence find the values of $u_1$ and $u_2$. <span class="marks">[4]</span>\n\n- Show that $\\alpha^2 = 4\\alpha -1$ and $\\beta^2 = 4\\beta - 1$. <span class="marks">[1]</span>\n\n- Hence show that $u_{n+2} = 4u_{n+1}-u_n$.<span class="marks">[4]</span>\n\n- Suppose that $u_n$ and $u_{n+1}$ are integers. Show that $u_{n+2}$ is also an integer.<span class="marks">[2]</span>\n\n- Hence show that $u_n$ is an integer for all $n \\in \\mathbb{Z}^+$.<span class="marks">[2]</span>\n\n\nNow consider the sequence defined by\n\n$$\nv_n = \\dfrac{\\sqrt{3}}{6}\\left(\\alpha^n + \\beta^n\\right).\n$$\n\n\n- Find the exact values of $v_1$ and $v_2$.<span class="marks">[4]</span>\n\n- Express $v_{n+2}$ in terms of $v_{n+1}$ and $v_n$.<span class="marks">[4]</span>\n\n- Hence show that $v_n$ is a multiple of $\\dfrac{\\sqrt{3}}{3}$ for all $n \\in \\mathbb{Z^+}$.<span class="marks">[4]</span>\n\n',
    markScheme:
      '\n- Completing the square for $x^2-4x+1=0$ we have\n\n  $$\n  \\begin{align*}\n  (x-2)^2-3&=0 \\\\[8pt]\n  (x-2)^2 &= 3 \\\\[8pt]\n  x - 2 &= \\pm\\sqrt{3} \\\\[8pt]\n  x &= 2 \\pm\\sqrt{3}\n  \\end{align*}\n  $$\n\n  Given that $\\alpha > \\beta$, we have $\\answer{\\alpha = 2 + \\sqrt{3} \\text{ and } \\beta = 2 - \\sqrt{3}}$\n- We have\n\n  $$\n  \\begin{align*}\n  u_1 &= \\dfrac{\\sqrt{3}}{6}\\left(\\alpha - \\beta\\right) \\\\[8pt]\n  &= \\dfrac{\\sqrt{3}}{6}\\left(2 + \\sqrt{3} - \\left(2 - \\sqrt{3}\\right)\\right) \\\\[8pt]\n  &\\hspace{-1.3em}\\tcbhighmath{u_1 = 1} \\hspace{3em}\\text{[By using G.D.C.]}\\\\[8pt]\n  u_2 &= \\dfrac{\\sqrt{3}}{6}\\left(\\alpha^2 - \\beta^2\\right) \\\\[8pt]\n  &= \\dfrac{\\sqrt{3}}{6}\\left(\\left(2 + \\sqrt{3}\\right)^2 - \\left(2 - \\sqrt{3}\\right)^2\\right) \\\\[8pt]\n  &\\hspace{-1.3em}\\tcbhighmath{u_2 = 4} \\hspace{3em}\\text{[By using G.D.C.]}\n  \\end{align*}\n  $$\n\n- Given that $\\alpha$ is a root of the quadratic equation, we get\n\n  $$\n  \\begin{align*}\n  \\alpha^2 - 4\\alpha + 1 &= 0 \\\\[12pt]\n  &\\hspace{-1.3em}\\tcbhighmath{\\alpha^2 = 4\\alpha -1}\n  \\end{align*}\n  $$\n\n  Similarly\n\n  $$\n  \\begin{align*}\n  \\beta^2 - 4\\beta + 1 &= 0 \\\\[12pt]\n  &\\hspace{-1.3em}\\tcbhighmath{\\beta^2 = 4\\beta -1}\\\\[-1cm]\n  \\end{align*}\n  $$\n\n- Using the expressions from part (c), we get\n\n  $$\n  \\begin{align*}\n  u_{n+2} &= \\dfrac{\\sqrt{3}}{6}\\left(\\alpha^{n+2}-\\beta^{n+2}\\right) \\\\[12pt]\n  &= \\dfrac{\\sqrt{3}}{6}\\left(\\alpha^{n}\\alpha^2-\\beta^{n}\\beta^2\\right) \\\\[12pt]\n  &= \\dfrac{\\sqrt{3}}{6}\\left(\\alpha^{n}(4\\alpha - 1)-\\beta^{n}(4\\beta - 1)\\right) \\\\[12pt]\n  &= \\dfrac{\\sqrt{3}}{6}\\left(4\\alpha^{n+1}-\\alpha^n - 4\\beta^{n+1}+\\beta^n\\right) \\\\[12pt]\n  &= \\dfrac{\\sqrt{3}}{6}\\left(4\\left(\\alpha^{n+1}-\\beta^{n+1}\\right)-\\left(\\alpha^n-\\beta^n\\right)\\right) \\\\[12pt]\n  &= \\dfrac{4\\sqrt{3}}{6}\\left(\\alpha^{n+1}-\\beta^{n+1}\\right)-\\dfrac{\\sqrt{3}}{6}(\\alpha^n - \\beta^n) \\\\[12pt]\n  &\\hspace{-2.25em}\\tcbhighmath{u_{n+2} = 4u_{n+1}-u_n}\n  \\end{align*}\n  $$\n\n- Using the results from part (d), we get\n\n  $$\n  \\begin{align*}\n  u_n \\text{ and } u_{n+1} &\\text{ are integers} \\\\[12pt]\n  -u_n \\text{ and } 4u_{n+1} &\\text{ are integers} \\\\[12pt] \n  4u_{n+1}-u_n &\\text{ is an integer} \\\\[12pt]\n  &\\hspace{-0.845cm}\\tcbhighmath{u_{n+2} \\text{ is an integer}}\n  \\end{align*}\n  $$\n\n- Using part (e), we get\n\n  $$\n  \\begin{align*}\n  u_1 &= 1 \\text{ is an integer (by part (b))} \\\\[12pt]\n  u_2 &= 4 \\text{ is an integer (by part (b))}\\\\[12pt] \n  u_3 & \\text{ is an integer (by part (e))} \\\\\n  & \\enskip \\vdots & \\\\[3pt]\n  u_n & \\text{ is an integer (by part (e))} \\\\[-9pt]\n  \\end{align*}\n  $$\n\n  Hence,$\\hspace{0.525em} we conclude that u_n is an integer for all n \\in \\mathbb{Z}^+$.$\n- We have\n\n  $$\n  \\begin{align*}\n  v_1 &= \\dfrac{\\sqrt{3}}{6}\\left(\\alpha + \\beta\\right) \\\\[8pt]\n  &= \\dfrac{\\sqrt{3}}{6}\\left(2 + \\sqrt{3} + 2 - \\sqrt{3}\\right) \\\\[8pt]\n  &\\hspace{-1em}\\tcbhighmath{v_1 = \\dfrac{2\\sqrt{3}}{3}} \\\\[8pt]\n  v_2 &= \\dfrac{\\sqrt{3}}{6}\\left(\\alpha^2 + \\beta^2\\right) \\\\[8pt]\n  &= \\dfrac{\\sqrt{3}}{6}\\left(\\left(2 + \\sqrt{3}\\right)^2 + \\left(2 - \\sqrt{3}\\right)^2\\right) \\\\[8pt]\n  &= \\dfrac{\\sqrt{3}}{6}\\left(4 + 4\\sqrt{3} + 3 + 4 -4\\sqrt{3} + 3\\right)\\\\[8pt]\n  &\\hspace{-1em}\\tcbhighmath{v_2 = \\dfrac{7\\sqrt{3}}{3}}\n  \\end{align*}\n  $$\n\n- By a procedure similar to part (d), we get\n\n  $$\n  \\begin{align*}\n  v_{n+2} &= \\dfrac{\\sqrt{3}}{6}\\left(\\alpha^{n+2}+\\beta^{n+2}\\right) \\\\[8pt]\n  &= \\dfrac{\\sqrt{3}}{6}\\left(\\alpha^{n}\\alpha^2+\\beta^{n}\\beta^2\\right) \\\\[8pt]\n  \\end{align*}\n  $$\n\n  From part (c) we have $\\alpha^2=4\\alpha-1$ and $\\beta^2=\\beta-1$.\n\n  $$\n  \\begin{align*}\n  v_{n+2} &= \\dfrac{\\sqrt{3}}{6}\\left(\\alpha^{n}(4\\alpha - 1)+\\beta^{n}(4\\beta - 1)\\right) \\\\[8pt]\n  &= \\dfrac{\\sqrt{3}}{6}\\left(4\\alpha^{n+1}-\\alpha^n + 4\\beta^{n+1}-\\beta^n\\right) \\\\[12pt]\n  &= \\dfrac{\\sqrt{3}}{6}\\left(4\\left(\\alpha^{n+1}+\\beta^{n+1}\\right)-\\left(\\alpha^n+\\beta^n\\right)\\right) \\\\[12pt]\n  &= \\dfrac{4\\sqrt{3}}{6}\\left(\\alpha^{n+1}+\\beta^{n+1}\\right)-\\dfrac{\\sqrt{3}}{6}(\\alpha^n + \\beta^n) \\\\[8pt]\n  &\\hspace{-2.05em}\\tcbhighmath{v_{n+2}= 4v_{n+1}-v_n}\n  \\end{align*}\n  $$\n\n- First suppose that $v_n$ and $v_{n+1}$ are both multiples of $\\dfrac{\\sqrt{3}}{3}$. Let $v_n=\\dfrac{p\\sqrt{3}}{3}$ and $v_{n+1}=\\dfrac{q\\sqrt{3}}{3}$ where $p,q \\in \\mathbb{Z}$. Using the result from part (h), we have\n\n  $$\n  \\begin{align*}\n  v_{n+2} &= \\dfrac{4q\\sqrt{3}}{3} - \\dfrac{p\\sqrt{3}}{3} \\\\[8pt]\n  &= (4q-p)\\dfrac{\\sqrt{3}}{3}\n  \\end{align*}\n  $$\n\n  If $v_n$ and $v_{n+1}$ are both multiples of $\\dfrac{\\sqrt{3}}{3}$, then $v_{n+2}$ is also. From part (g) we notice that $v_1$ and $v_2$ are both multiples of $\\dfrac{\\sqrt{3}}{3}$.\n  Therefore,$\\hspace{0.525em}  v_n \\text{is a multiple of } \\dfrac{\\sqrt{3}}{3} \\text{ for all } n \\in \\mathbb{Z}^+ $\n',
