    content:
      'Consider three planes represented by the following system of equations:\n\n$$\n\\begin{align*}\n\\Pi_1: -2x + ay + 4z &= 2 \\\\[6pt]\n\\Pi_2: x + by - 2z &= -1 \\\\[6pt]\n\\Pi_3: 2x - y + cz &= 3\n\\end{align*}\n$$\n\nWhere $a,b,c \\in \\mathbb{R}$.\n\n- State the values of $a$, $b$ and $c$ for which\n  \n  - The system has infinite solutions.\n  - The system is inconsistent. <span class="marks">[7]</span>\n\n\n- In the case where the system has infinite solutions, describe the geometric relationship between the three planes. <span class="marks">[2]</span>\n\n- In the case where the system is inconsistent, identify one of the geometric relationships that could exist between the three planes.  <span class="marks">[2]</span>\n\n',
    markScheme:
      '\n- If we convert the given system of equations into an augmented matrix, we have\n  ![SkillUpp Image](https://assets.revisionvillage.com/public/question/e8f9c4b4-8442-45bf-8389-6c5abb138ec8/images/3f804c21-6625-4b1d-a6cc-56f4ed650a1e/aa1012a.PNG)\n\n\n  Hence, using the method of Gaussian Elimination, we get\n  ![SkillUpp Image](https://assets.revisionvillage.com/public/question/e8f9c4b4-8442-45bf-8389-6c5abb138ec8/images/da6543cf-8657-43e1-8040-dec0d15cf8cf/aa1012b.PNG)\n\n\n  \n  - From row 2, if the system has infinite solutions, we must have $a + 2b = 0$.\n    This implies that if $a = -2b$, there are infinite solutions to the system.\n    However, we also note from row 3, that if $a - 1 = 0$ and $c + 4 = 0$, then the system is inconsistent. In this case we have $a = 1$ and $c = -4$.\n    There are infinite solutions to the system if $a = -2b$, $c \\in \\mathbb{R}$ unless $a=1$, $b=-0.5$ and $c=-4$.\n  - As noted in part (i), if $a = 1$ and $c = -4$, the system is inconsistent.\n    However, we also note that if $a \\neq 1$ and $c = -4$, Gaussian Elimination leads to\n    ![SkillUpp Image](https://assets.revisionvillage.com/public/question/e8f9c4b4-8442-45bf-8389-6c5abb138ec8/images/7cd78d6b-425a-48e9-b2b6-e41b3b6fdb70/aa1021b.png)\n\n\n    In this case, we can also have an inconsistent system.\n    From part (a), if $a = -2b$ then the system is consistent (has infinite solutions), however consider when $a \\neq -2b$.\n    It follows that $a+2b =k$, where $k \\neq 0$, this leads to\n    ![SkillUpp Image](https://assets.revisionvillage.com/public/question/e8f9c4b4-8442-45bf-8389-6c5abb138ec8/images/757dcf45-e7bd-4832-b55b-c311d8f0a8d8/aa1012a2.png)\n\n\n    Using row 2\n\n    $$\n    \\begin{align*}\n    ky &=0 \\\\\n    \\intertext{As $k \\neq 0$ then}\n    y &= 0 \n    \\end{align*}\n    $$\n\n    Using row 3, this value of $y$ shows an inconsistency as shown below.\n\n    $$\n    \\begin{align*}\n    (a-1)y &=5 \\\\\n    (a-1)\\times0 &= 5 \\\\\n    0 &= 5 \n    \\end{align*}\n    $$\n\n    Hence...\n    $\\answer{\\text{The system is inconsistent if } a = 1 \\text{ and } c = -4, b \\in \\mathbb{R} \\text{ or if } a \\neq 1, a \\neq -2b \\text{ and } c = -4.}$\n\n- From (a) (i), we note that $\\Pi_1$ is a multiple of $\\Pi_2$. They are therefore equations representing the same plane.\n  $\\answer{\\Pi_1 \\text{ and } \\Pi_2 \\text{ are coincidental, }\\Pi_3 \\text{ intersects both planes in a straight line.}}$\n- In total there are 4 different geometric realtionships between the planes when the system is inconsistent.\n  First, from part (a) (i) we note that the system is inconsistent if $a=1$, $b=-0.5$ and $c=-4$. In this case,\n  $\\hspace{0.525em}\\tcbhighmath{\\Pi_1 \\text{ and } \\Pi_2 \\text{ are coincidental and } \\Pi_3 \\text{ is parallel to both planes.}}\\hspace{0.525em}$\n  Second, from (a) (ii), we have one scenario where $a=1$, $b \\neq -0.5$ and $c=-4$. In this case,\n  $\\hspace{0.525em}\\tcbhighmath{\\Pi_1 \\text{ and } \\Pi_3 \\text{ are parallel and } \\Pi_2 \\text{ intersects both planes.}}\\hspace{0.525em}$\n  Thirdly, if $a \\neq 1$, $b=-0.5$ and $c=-4$,\n  $\\hspace{0.525em}\\tcbhighmath{\\Pi_2 \\text{ and } \\Pi_3 \\text{ are parallel and } \\Pi_1 \\text{ intersects both planes.}}\\hspace{0.525em}$\n  Finally, if $a \\neq 1$, $a \\neq -2b$ and $c=-4$, then $\\Pi_1$ intersects $\\Pi_2$ on a line, $\\Pi_1$ intersects $\\Pi_3$ on a different line and $\\Pi_2$ intersects $\\Pi_3$ on another different line. Additionally,$\\hspace{0.525em}\\tcbhighmath{\\text{All three of these lines of intersection are parallel.}}\\hspace{0.525em}$\n',
